SYMPTOM_TEXT: Got the shot called Recombinant Zoster vaccine (Zostavax?) on 11 July 2019.  Two weeks later I developed myalgia along my spine, beginning in the lower back and progressing to the neck and front and back shoulder area.  It was severe enough to interfere with my normal activities which include swimming and walking.  After a month I went to my health care provider who took me off atorvastatin as this can either cause or aggravate myalgia.  The myalgia disappated but continued for 2 months before finally disappearing.  I am pretty sure the shingles shot caused the myalgia as I have spoken to 2 other people who had the same reaction, although theirs occurred more immediately after the shot and continued for a much shorter period of time.  I have suggested they file their own reports.
OTHER_MEDS: atorvastatin, fish oil, calcium, D3 , CoQ 10

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient said that after the shot redness and puffiness occurred. He said the puffiness was pretty severe. Today he said it is much better and just a little puffy and a little pain at injection site.

started with itching in arm that shot was given then spread to whole body within an hour. by that night hives started breaking out all over my body. this continued for 4 weeks. I took over the counter allergy med ..zertec D in the day and benadryl at night to be able to not be so uncomfotable. dr is a dermatologist who recomended this treatment . at week 4-6 i still got hives but only here and there and especially after a hot shower

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient said she started feeling flu-like symptoms shortly after getting the vaccine.  She felt the worst 11/28/19.  Could barely get out of bed.  Felt hot and clammy but never took her temperature to see if there was a fever.  She said she is feeling better today, 12/1/19.  She said she felt poorly after the first vaccine, but nothing like the way she felt after this second dose.  She also had swelling/redness and pain at the injection site.  It was red at the site, about the size of a ping pong ball, then about 2 inches "white" around the red, almost like a bulls-eye.  She said had she not known flu-like symptoms were an expected reaction, she would have gone to the doctor.

Patient passed out after receiving the flu shot.  Fortunately, he sat down in a chair before passing out.  I placed my hand on his shoulder and asked him if he was okay and he woke up.  Patient had indicated that he had never had that type of reaction to a vaccine before.  I asked him to remain seated for at least 15 minutes before leaving.  After about 20 minutes, he left the pharmacy and indicated that he was okay.

She felt very anxious beforehand and got dizzy with hot flashes after receiving the vaccine. She sat on the floor afterwards and drank some orange juice and I gave her a cold pack for her neck and a fan to cool her off. After about 30 minutes,  her daughter came to pick her up. She was feeling a little better and her daughter drove her home.
PRIOR_VAX: dizziness

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The shots appear to have triggered an autoimmune resonse which is still present. Shortly after I received the shots I develped mononucleosis and strep throat. I have been experiencing chronic recurring viral infections since. I have been unable to exercise or perform strenous physical activity, when I do a viral infection manifests. I have had to sleep at least 10 hours each night just to be able to function and get through the day. I have had a difficult time interacting with others and now have a low stress tolerance. I was healthy before the shots and I have felt terrible ever recieving the shots.
LAB_DATA: Mononucleosis, Strep throat, Positive ANA,  total cholesterol of 102,  elevated liver markers, low vitamn d, positive HS1, low adrenaline, low glutamate.

Co-suspect products included Hepatitis B vaccine for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included hemodialysis (in 2008, the patient had an initiated of hemodialysis). Concurrent medical conditions included end stage renal disease, diabetes mellitus, lymphoma (status post chemotherapy in 2009), coronary artery disease and cirrhosis of liver without mention of alcohol.   On an unknown date, the patient received Hepatitis B vaccine at an unknown dose and Hepatitis B vaccine at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Hepatitis B vaccine and Hepatitis B vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and hepatitis b (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and hepatitis b were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure and hepatitis b to be related to Hepatitis B vaccine and Hepatitis B vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a 80-year-old male patient who was vaccinated with unspecified Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to case 1 of table 1 reported in this literature article. The patient had medical history significant for end-stage renal disease ESRD; diabetes mellitus; lymphoma (status post chemotherapy in 2009); coronary artery disease. On unspecified date in 2008, the patient had an initiated of hemodialysis. At the time of initiation, the patient was considered HBV- susceptible (anti-HBs and HBsAg negative) but failed to respond to a full HBV vaccination series. In 2009, HBV testing confirmed he was HBV susceptible. No information on patient's family history or concomitant condition was provided. On unspecified date in 2010, the patient had received unspecified Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On unspecified date, unknown period after vaccination and in between during this period July 2011 and January 2014, the patient was on hemodialysis (HD), the patient was on likely infectious and not on HBV isolation.  On unspecified date in between 2011 and 2014, the patient potential exposure period was elsewhere (i.e travel history). The patient had an HBV serology, which showed that First known negative HBsAg (July 2010); Last known negative HBsAg (July 2012); First known positive HBsAg (January 2014); First known negative anti- HBs (December 2010); Last known negative anti- HBs (July 2011); First known positive anti- HBs (before HBsAg seroconversion) January 2012 (negative in January 2014); First known positive total anti-HBc ( February 2014 (tested negative June 2010). In January 2012, the case patient was anti-HBs positive and HBsAg negative and considered HBV immune.  On unspecified date in 2013, the patient had hospitalization due to multiple invasive procedures including HD, surgery. On an unspecified date in January 2014, the patient had an HBV Isolation precautions were implemented. Further HBV testing revealed that he had chronic HBV infection (negative immunoglobulin M [IgM], anti-HBc, positive total anti-HBc (February 2014 (tested negative June 2010), positive hepatitis B e antigen, First known positive HBsAg (January 2014). On an unspecified February 2014, the patient's HBV serology showed that the patient had a high HBV DNA levels of 593,045,000 copies/mL [UltraQuant] on and on unspecified date in 2014, the patient had an 101,898,000 IU/mL [AmpliPrep/cobas-Roche]. On an unspecified May 2013, the patient's highest known ALT/AST: 19/54. The patient had also done HBsAg testing by platform such in January 2014: positive; Siemens Advia Centaur XP: not tested; VITROS in March 2014: positive. Given the unusual serologic picture of HBsAg seroconversion several months after the initial laboratory evidence of exposure to HBV infection (newly anti-HBs positive in January 2012) paired with high HBV DNA levels, infection with an HBV mutant strain was suspected. Sequencing of HBV DNA revealed a genotype H infection with a sP127L mutation in the "a" determinant region. The patient also had other HBV testing's which showed that the sequencing of HBV DNA revealed a genotype H infection with a sp127l mutation in the "a" determinant region. The screening of potentially exposed hemodialysis patient in 2014 did not reveal new HBV infections. The source of HBV infection was not discovered.  The case patient died in 2014 from complications of ESRD and non-alcoholic related cirrhosis. It was unknown whether his death was related to HBV infection.  This case considered as suspected vaccination failure due to onset of time was unknown. This case has been considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure. The author commented, "It was unknown whether his death was related to HBV infection. To our knowledge, there has been no documented hemodialysis-related transmission of a mutant strain of HBV." The author concluded "Mutant HBV infections should be suspected in patients who test HBsAg negative and concurrently test positive for HBV DNA at high levels. Dialysis providers should consider using HBsAg assays that can also detect mutant HBV strains for routine HBV testing." This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in this literature article. Non-reassuring fetal heart tones; Fetus intrauterine growth restrictions and failure to progress; Hypospadias; Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Neonate's birth weight was 2013 g; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 21-Nov-2019 and with additional information received on 25-Nov-2019 (being processed together), concerning a male neonatal subject whose mother was 27-year-old pregnant, female subject, of body weight: 210 Ibs, height: 68 in and body mass index (BMI) 31.9  enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study. The subject's father was 30-year-old.  The subject's mother had three previous pregnancies with three spontaneous abortions. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The subject's mother had no history of offspring with MCM. The subject's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The mother's current condition include obesity with BMI 30+ and hypertension. The mother's historical vaccine included TDap (diphtheria vaccine toxoid, pertussis vaccine acellular and tetanus vaccine toxoid) as vaccine. The mother's concomitant medications included Baby Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid) and labetalol, both used for hypertension and prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins and minerals) for obstetrical (OB) care.   The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was on an unspecified date in 2019. Estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 25-Nov-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 22-May-2019, the subject's mother underwent first trimester screen and it was noted that the foetus was positive for Down Syndrome. However, later the mother underwent MaterniT 21 and it was within normal limits. No MCMs noted.  On 29-May-2019, the subject's mother underwent MaterniT 21 and no MCMs were noted.  On 09-Oct-2019, at approximately 33 weeks of gestation, the subject's mother was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIVc) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261207, dose: 0.5 mL, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.   On an unspecified date, pregnancy status of subject's mother was collected and non-reassuring fetal heart tones (FHT), failure to progress (FTP) and fetus intrauterine growth restrictions (IUGR) were reported as pregnancy complications.   On 06-Nov-2019, at approximately 37.3 weeks of gestation, the mother delivered a live male neonate via caesarean method. The neonate's birth weight was 2013 grams, body length and head circumference were not reported. The reported appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute was 8, at five minutes was 9 and no data was provided at 10 minutes. MCM identified at birth was hypospadias. As reported, contributing factor to neonate's hypospadias was hypertension in mother. Etiology was unknown, however, it was reported that it was possibly genetic as possible anti-androgenic exposures. It was reported that gestational age for origin of the defect was 7 to 12 weeks and that the origin of the defect was prior the mother's vaccination. Other factors contributing to the MCM were unknown.  At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the events of low birth weight baby, hypospadias, non-reassuring fetal heart tones and fetus intrauterine growth restrictions and failure to progress was not reported.  The events of 'low birth weight baby', 'hypospadias', 'non-reassuring fetal heart tones' and 'fetus intrauterine growth restrictions and failure to progress' were assessed as serious (medically significant).   The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIVc.  This case is linked to case number 201906264 (corresponding mother case).  Company Comment: The male neonatal subject was delivered as low birth weight baby with nonreassuring foetal heart rate pattern, foetal growth restriction and hypospadias after foetal exposure during pregnancy (at approximately 33 weeks of gestation) with the suspect product, Flucelvax QIV. Chronology is plausible for all events except for hypospadias. Gestational age for origin of hypospadias was 7 to 12 weeks, making temporal relationship incompatible. Mother's medical history of three spontaneous abortions, hypertension and obesity (body mass index 31.9) may provide alternative aetiology for the events. Causality was also confounded with concomitant medications, Baby Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid) and labetalol. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. For the events low birth weight baby nonreassuring foetal heart rate pattern and foetal growth restriction, causal role of the suspect product cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as unlikely related. Causality for the event hypospadias is assessed as not related.; Sender's Comments: The male neonatal subject was delivered as low birth weight baby with nonreassuring foetal heart rate pattern, foetal growth restriction and hypospadias after foetal exposure during pregnancy (at approximately 33 weeks of gestation) with the suspect product, Flucelvax QIV. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Very high glucose (>200 mg/dl) starting two days after the flu vaccine that persisted for two days and was dangerous due to the risk of DKA and history of vitreous hemorrhage and DME. Upper respiratory illness.   The manufacturer should provide a warning to diabetics and disclose the efficacy for the current year (a mere 9% for 2019). The amount of mercury in this flu vaccine should be disclosed and the ingredients on the CDC website should be accurate and not omit ingredients (eg, the neurotoxin mercury in any amount). A risk benefit analysis should be done to determine whether their is net benefit for the flu vaccine considering it has the most VAERS complaints of any vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Had an injection for DME approximately one month later. It's unclear what impact the high glucose may have had on the DME but it's hardly desirable to be spiking that high after a flu shot with extremely low efficacy. I have excellent control of my glucose (A1C 5.4) and monitor myself very closely with a CGM and predictive software. My glucose is never as high for as long as it was after this flu shot.
OTHER_MEDS: Tresiba Novolog Regular Insulin Levothyroxine Multivitamin Magnesium

thalamic infarct on the left lateral thalamus; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a male patient (pt) of unknown age. The pt's concurrent conditions and medical history were not provided.  In or around 12-DEC-2016 the pt was vaccinated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date (reported as " Shortly after receiving vaccine"), the pt experienced shortness of breath, chest pain and numbness and tingling on the right side of his arm extending to his fingers. The patient was also having weakness on the right lower extremity which was causing him to walk tilted and fall. The pt was hospitalized and diagnosed with thalamic infarct on the left lateral thalamus. In addition, it was reported that the pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. The pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the pt suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury (disability). At the time of the report, the outcome of thalamic infarction was not recovered.  The reporter considered thalamic infarction and emotional distress to be related to Zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX).  Upon internal review, thalamic infarction was considered to be an important medical event , and due to the limiting, permanent and incurable injuries was also considered disabling.

Burning sensation; Sensitive skin; Does not feel the area unless something is touching the area; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of burning sensation in a 66-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. In November 2019, between 1 and 2 weeks after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced burning sensation, sensitive skin and numbness localized. On an unknown date, the outcome of the burning sensation was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the sensitive skin and numbness localized were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the burning sensation, sensitive skin and numbness localized to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The patient reported for himself. The patient had the Shingrix vaccine in the right arm, approximately at the end of October 2019 or early part of November 2019. He did not know exact date. About 8 to 10 days before the reporting date, the patient developed sensitive skin about a quarter inch below his rib cage. The patient described it as, the area was about four inches wide and run horizontal. The area was a football shape cut in half that tapered to a point along the sides of his body. It was in the center of his rib cage area. The patient also stated that, he did not feel the area unless something touch it such as his shirt or sheet.  He described these symptoms as a burning sensation, the area was not red and did not itch. He further stated that, the sensation moved down his rib cage. The patient mentioned this to his physician but his physician did not know what it could be. The patient did not have lot number. The patient consented to follow up and provided his physician's details also.

A couple of days following patient's vaccination of DTaP, he was complaining of nausea and stomach pain. He rested for a couple of days, but then on Monday the 28th, he began to throw up bright green fluid. We thought he might have a flu, so we waited 24 hours to see if the vomiting would stop. On Tuesday the 29th, he threw up once in the morning. He continued to rest that day, but he refused to drink or eat anything. On Wednesday the 30th, he was very lethargic and would only drink a few sips at a time. I noticed that he was showing signs of dehydration, so we tried to get him to drink more fluids, but he would resist. On Thursday the 31st, I took him into Urgent Care, as his symptoms weren't improving and he was indicating a worsening pain in his stomach. They sent us to the ER, where they took a CT scan, which showed that his appendix was inflamed. From the time we left the CT and up to surgery, his appendix had ruptured. Due to the contamination in his system, he stayed in the hospital for a week.
LAB_DATA: 10/31/19 Appendectomy and related tests throughout the week 11/6/19 in the evening--discharged from hospital

Got my second shot on 30 November 2019 around 11:30 am.  Experienced stronger side effects than from the first shot.  The initial side effects were the ones documented as common; muscle and joint pain, fever, headache, tired, loss of appetite, swollen glands in neck (flue like symptoms).  These started early afternoon on the 30th.  The fever subsided around 2 am on Dec 1st.   I then started to experience a side effect I did not see identified for this vaccine.  I noticed on Dec 1st that my urine was darker in color than normal.  It was more yellow / brown in color.  At first, I did not pay much attention as I figured that because the vaccine caused me to lose my appetite I had not been eating or drinking as much.  I figured my urine was just more concentrated due to drinking less water although it did have a slightly brown tinge rather than just a darker yellow that is more characteristic for me when I start to get dehydrated.   The next morning, December 2nd my urine was a very dark (slightly reddish) brown color.  (It may have been this color during the night but I did not check when emptied my bladder at night as only have a night light in the bathroom at night so don?t turn on a room light.)  I did not feel like I was dehydrated or thirsty.  I was still drinking some water because that is what I normally do but not as much as I was not thirsty.  I did not feel the urge to urinate as frequently that day.  When I urinated late afternoon, my urine was still a very dark (slightly reddish) brown color.  After urinating the water in the bowel looked like the color after having diarrhea (but of course no solid matter in this case).  At that point I started drinking much more water regardless of thirst.   I am continuing to monitor the situation and if it has not cleared up by the end of the day on December 3rd, I will go to see a doctor on December 4th.  It is my assumption that I have blood in my urine (but it is not fresh red) or perhaps bilirubin.  Unfortunately, I did not think to get a urine sample for testing (I don?t have a sterile container to collect it in).  I have not experienced pain or discomfort when urinating.  I have no health problems and am not on any medications.  So far on December 3rd my urine color has not been the very dark brown.  It has lightened to more of a dark yellow brown.  I am continuing to hydrate more heavily.   NDC number: 58160-0823-11  Expiration date of lot is 04/24/2022.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I started out with soreness in my left arm late in the afternoon on Sunday (12/1).  By bedtime, I had trouble lifting my arm up.  I also had headaches and was very tired.  By Monday, I woke up (after 8 hours of sleep) totally exhausted and my arm was still painful but I didn't actually pay attention to the area where I received the shot.   By mid-day Monday, I was having chills and felt like I had a fever.  I was at work and didn't have a thermometer but took an Advil.  I went home by 3:00, totally achy, with off and on chills and my arm was hurting even more than the day before.  I slept for about 2.5 hours.  I took my temperature when I got up, which was 99.5.  I got up and had dinner and went to bed around 10:30 taking a Tylenol PM before going to bed.  I stayed home today (Tuesday) as I had off and on chills and achyness all over.  When I hopped into the shower at 11:00, I noticed that my left arm where I received the injections was seriously swollen, hot and a large rash developed with a red rash line that went down my arm.  I went to a Clinic to see what was going on and was prescribed Clindamycin (300MG)  Separately, my wife had sent photos of my arm to a friend who is a doctor of infectious diseases   as well as my physician, Dr.  Both pointed me to an article which pointed out that all of the symptoms I was experiencing was an infrequent reaction to the PS23 vaccine and I should NOT take the antibiotic (Clindamycin).  I only took 1 pill and have stopped treatment.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Headache

I got my seasonal flu shot at an outdoor fall festival. on September 28th. The flu shots were sponsored by the local Hospital. I found out later the shots were being given by student nurses. I was asked to sit while she stood. I noticed the shot was given much higher on my right shoulder than usual. There was no pain at that time. My shoulder did not start hurting until early evening the next day, Sept. 29th. I awoke several times that night with pain. The next morning it really hurt to move. I thought it might just be a regular but extreme reaction to the shot. I waited until the end of the week and contacted my doctor. I also contacted the hospital to inform them of my reaction to the shot.  At the doctor appointment Oct. 9th my doctor said there was not much he could do and to take ibuprofen. It did nothing for the pain. I contacted my doctor Oct 29 with terrible pain and sleepless nights. There was also increasing weakness. The doctor ordered an MRI which was done Nov. 7th. It showed a supraspinatus tendon rotator cuff tear and fluid visible in the subacromial /subdeltoid bursa. My doctor sent me to physical therapy which started Nov. 19th. I have had 6 sessions with no relief. I recontacted my doctor and he has referred me to an orthopedic doctor. An appointment has not as yet been scheduled. I have pain with any movement, extreme weakness and a constant ache even when not moving.
LAB_DATA: MRI- supraspinatus tendon rotator cuff tear with fluid visible in the subacromial/subdeltoid bursa

Dizziness(Felt dizzy); Turned blue; Distress; Vagal Reaction; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of dizziness in a 13-year-old female patient who received HPV 16-18 (HPV vaccine unknown) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received HPV vaccine unknown at an unknown dose. On an unknown date, less than a day after receiving HPV vaccine unknown, the patient experienced dizziness (serious criteria hospitalization), cyanosis (serious criteria hospitalization), emotional distress (serious criteria hospitalization) and vagal reaction (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the dizziness, cyanosis, emotional distress and vagal reaction were unknown.   The reporter considered the dizziness, cyanosis, emotional distress and vagal reaction to be related to HPV vaccine unknown.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described occurrence of dizziness; fetal position, turned blue, vagal reaction and  distress, in a 13- year-old patient who was vaccinated with unspecified human papilloma virus (HPV) vaccine and unspecified meningococcal vaccine (MENO vaccine) (manufacturer unknown for both) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to figure 2 reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of a descriptive study that was conducted to characterized public posts about the HPV vaccine and quantify the impact of sentiment and context on engagement via likes. By using analytic method at the beginning 30th April, 2018, through 20th August, 2018, publicly available posts (n = 29,763 posts) were collected although the final sample included posts that were created as far back as November 2, 2011, because API did not have a retrospective time limit on data collection. For the study inclusion criteria included, unique (not duplicates post, languages post, working link URL, text mentions HPV, specific to the HPV vaccine. Out of total 29,763, of 3, 378 posts were eligible. Our final analytic sample include 360 posts (as coded non-purposive post]. No information on patient's medical history or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On unspecified date, at the age of 13 years, the patient had received unspecified HPV vaccine and unspecified meningococcal vaccine in the morning (administration site and route unspecified; dosage unknown; batch number not provided for both). On an unspecified date, at the age of 13 years, on the same day after vaccination, when the patient was leaving, the patient felt dizzy got into the car and went into a fetal position and turned blue. The patient's parent notified to the doctor office they ran out and started examination of the patient. The examination revealed the patient's heart rate dropped to 52 beats per minute and the patient was in distress. The patient was taken to hospital by ambulance and was hooked into an electrocardiogram (EKG) and blood work (result not provided for both). It was reported that the pedestrian said that it was a vaccine reaction, however hospital was saying that the patient had vagal reaction and discrediting vaccine reaction. This case was posted by friend of patient's parent on social media. This case has been considered as serious due to Hospitalization. Treatment was unknown.  The outcome of the event was not reported. The author commented, "The final analytic sample comprised 360 unique posts from 292 users. Of the 1,200 randomly sampled posts, 979 (81.6%) had active links, and one in three (n = 360 out of 979; 36.8% posts with working links) was relevant to the HPV vaccine. The author concluded, "On social media, discussions about HPV vaccination are often characterized by emotionally charged expressions of personal beliefs, personal narratives, information, and misinformation. Pro-vaccine posts are more prevalent on social media and anti-vaccine posts have higher engagement. We found that personal narratives about HPV vaccination were more likely to promote anti-vaccine sentiment and were produced more often by individual users who were not health-related or health professionals. At the same time, we observed that posts from health-related sources were predominantly in favor of the HPV vaccine, but posted pro-vaccine personal narratives far less often than information or resources. Provaccine narratives tended to show individuals who had recently received the vaccine, but rarely provided long-term details about their experience with vaccination, such as recognition or appreciation of an individual's personal role in life-long cancer prevention, highlighting stark contrasts with the depth and scope of details included in anti-vaccine personal narrative posts. Within the context of HPV vaccination, our research contributes meaningfully to gaps in the study of misinformation on social media by offering an estimate for the prevalence of misinformation on social media, as quantified by the proportion of anti-vaccine posts, and we also identified important characteristics of misinformation-containing anti-vaccine posts. More broadly, by equipping Provaccine advocates with concrete recommendations to improve the engagement, via likes, of their social media content, our findings may apply to combatting vaccine hesitancy in general, an emerging and global health threat identified recently by the World Health Organization.  With sufficient resources, organizations such as patient advocacy groups, health departments, and government agencies could create a portfolio of positive pro-vaccine narratives with accompanying visuals (e.g., photo) to disseminate, filling an essentially unoccupied field of content". Pt received Shingrix dose on 12/2/19 at approx. 7pm.  Pt developed extreme weakness and could not stand by 12noon on 12/3/19.  Pt was transported by ambulance to local hospital and presented with extreme weakness, inability to stand, 101 degree fever, chills, and headache.  Tests were done, with no other obvious explanation for symptoms. As of this morning, lab values had not been returned yet, everything on heart monitor is O.K., his blood pressure is within a normal range.  The hospitalist is running cultures to attempt to identify any other possible infectious source.  Pt. is still in observation unit of hospital, but is much improved, is able to walk, but headache still remains.  Pt's PCP told pt that a small number of patients react negatively to Shingrix.  All this info was relayed to me by pt's wife, on 12/4/19 at about 08:30 am.

Pre-eclampsia; Dysmature placenta; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case initially received on 27-Nov-2019, concerning a 33-year-old female pregnant subject of body weight 179 lbs, height 63 inches and body mass index (BMI) 31.7, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy. The subject's partner age was 34.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject two previous pregnancies with one spontaneous abortion and one full term live birth with no birth defects. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 18-Feb-2019. The subject's estimated date of delivery (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 25-Nov-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   The subject's historical condition included yeast since 30-Apr-2019 to 10-May-2019. The subject's current condition included hypertension since 13-Jun-2019. The subject's historical drug included Terazol (terconazole) for yeast. The subject's concomitant medications included prenatal vitamins (unspecified minerals and vitamins) for pregnancy and labetalol for hypertension.  On 19-Apr-2019, the subject haemoglobin (Hgb) electrophoresis and no MCMs were noted.  On 17-May-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and panorama. No MCMs were noted.  On 11-Oct-2019, at approximately 33 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIVc) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 261218, dose: 0.5 mL, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.  On an unspecified date, the patient experienced pre-eclampsia and dysmature placenta, reported as pregnancy complication.  at approximately 37 weeks of gestation, the subject gave live birth to a male neonate vaginally. The characteristics of the neonate included birth weight: 3070 grams, head circumference: 35.6 cm and length: 50.2 cm. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 9 at one minute and 9 at five minutes. No major congenital malformations (MCMs) were identified at the time of birth.   At the time of the initial reporting, the outcome for the events of pre-eclampsia and dysmature placenta was not reported.  The events of pre-eclampsia and dysmature placenta were considered as serious due to criterion of medical significance per company.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIVc.  Company Comment: The subject experienced pre-eclampsia and placental disorder after unknown amount of time after vaccination with the suspect product, Flucelvax QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at 33 weeks of gestation. Chronology is unclear but plausible. Medical history of hypertension and obesity (body mass index 31.7) may provide alternative aetiology for the events. Causality was also confounded by therapy with concomitant medication, labetalol.  Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events pre-eclampsia and placental disorder is assessed as unlikely related.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced pre-eclampsia and placental disorder after unknown amount of time after vaccination with the suspect product, Flucelvax QIV. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within about 4-5 hours after the shot the site became very sore and continued to increase in intensity, dull intense soreness. This is unusual for me as I do not get sore arms of any note for other vaccines and also did the usual series of pushups to ward that off.   More concerning was around 10pm or later when going to bed I developed shivers without even feeling cold. No temperature that I could find with the IR thermometer. The shivers went on until I fell asleep, maybe 20-30 minutes. Covering with a blanket seemed to lessen it. Again I never felt cold, just started shivering.  Shivers were completely gone when I awoke the next morning. The arm soreness had decreased and as I used it throughout the day lessened. Soreness was gone by late the following evening.
redness and swelling  went to doctor feeling better put on doxycycline

muscle pain top of her shoulders on both sides; chills; muscle pain/neck muscle pain; could barely move her; prevented her from doing her normal daily activities like working/herself up with a pillow to move in bed; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of muscle pain in a 56-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 2nd October 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 4th October 2019, 2 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced muscle pain and mobility decreased. On 5th October 2019, the patient experienced shoulder pain and chills. In October 2019, the patient experienced activities of daily living impaired. The patient was treated with ibuprofen (Advil). On an unknown date, the outcome of the muscle pain, mobility decreased, shoulder pain, chills and activities of daily living impaired were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the muscle pain, mobility decreased, shoulder pain, chills and activities of daily living impaired to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix in right arm. After receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced terrible neck muscle pain on one side of her neck which lasted a couple of days and she could barely move her neck.  The following day, the muscle pain moved to the other side of her neck and then migrated to the top of her shoulders on both sides and she had chills.  The patient took Advil around the clock for the pain which she typically did not take but the side effects prevented her from doing her normal daily activities like working out which she typically did daily.  She had to prop herself up with a pillow to move in bed. All of her symptoms resolved and she stopped taking the Advil. The patient reported that, she was 64 inches in height and 110 pounds in weight and she had concerned that, she could have received too much medication in the vaccination for her size.  The reporter consented to follow up.

The subject's concomitant medications included Ferralet (ascorbic acid, cyanobalamin, docusate sodium, ferrous gluconate, folic acid and iron pentacarbonyl) for pregnancy, Lexapro (escitalopram oxalate) for anxiety and depression and prenatal gummy (minerals NOS, vitamins NOS) as a pregnancy care. Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 27-Nov-2019, concerning a female neonate whose mother was a 27-year-old, pregnant female subject of body weight: 160 lbs, height: 63 inches and body mass index (BMI): 28.3, enrolled in  a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy. The subject's father was a 26-year-old.  The subject's mother medical history included increased BMI. The mother's concomitant medications included Prenatal (ascorbic acid, betacarotene, calcium carbonate, colecalciferol, cyanocobalamin, dl-alpha tocopheryl acetate, ferrous fumarate, folic acid, nicotinamide, pyridoxine hydrochloride, riboflavin, thiamine mononitrate, zinc oxide) for pregnancy.  The subject's mother had no previously pregnancies. The subject's mother had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The subject's mother last menstrual period (LMP) date was 08-Feb-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The subject's mother estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 15-Nov-2019 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 17-Nov-2019.   On 12-Apr-2019, the mother underwent ultrasound scan and MCM was noted.   On 03-May-2019, the mother underwent first trimester screen and no MCM was noted.   On 18-Oct-2019, approximately at 36 weeks of gestation, the subject's mother was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIV) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 261226, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunization.  four days after vaccination, at gestational age of 36.3 weeks, the subject's mother vaginally delivered a normal, female neonate of body weight 2991 grams, head circumference 34.9 cm and body length 48.3 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 9 at one minute and 9 at five minutes. APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. There was no MCM identified at birth.  The event of 'premature birth' is considered serious due to criterion of medically significance, per company.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  This case is linked to cases 201907041 (mother case).  Company comment: Subject's mother received Flucelvax at approximately 36 weeks of gestation. Four days after vaccination, at gestational age of 36.3 weeks, a neonate was delivered, which was reported as preterm birth. Causality assessment is confounded by subject's increased BMI (28.3) and use of concomitant medications. Nevertheless, causal involvement of vaccine is not excluded, therefore the event of preterm birth is assessed as possibly related to Flucelvax. Foetal exposure is assessed as unrelated to the suspect product per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: Subject's mother received Flucelvax at approximately 36 weeks of gestation. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received first shingrix vaccine on 9/21/19. On 12/4/19, patient was diagnosed with shingles by FNP-C. Provider requested that this adverse event be reported to VAERS.

After each vaccine, I became acutely ill. I have progressively become worse. Don't feel well in general, tired all the time, joint pain and muscle aches. I was very healthy before the series and have since been diagnosed with multiple autoimmune disorders including fibromyalgia, POTS and another, unknown autoimmune type disorder that mimics rheumatoid arthritis but all tests for RA have come back negative. I have chronic pain with no explanation as to why. I was diagnosed with premature ovarian failure and had to take fertility meds to get pregnant. Previous to the series I had at least 10 normal annual pap smears. After the series, I had an abnormal pap which resulted in a biopsy then a LEEP which led to my cervix being removed for high grade dysplasia that couldn't be removed. I developed endometriosis that I didn't have beforehand. I have lived in pain and am constantly tired for the last 13 years. I was one of the first people to receive the series.
LAB_DATA: Multiple rheumatology, endocrinology and cardiology appointments between 2006 and 2019 GYN- blood work, ultrasounds, hysterosalpingography, pap smears, pathology reports from cervical biopsy, LEEP, hysterectomy- all 2006-2012

Also reports dysphagia, "like lump in chest after swallowing, that might feel better after vomiting."  She has not vomited and has no specific nausea.  Ate some rice and drank water today without specific problems.  No diarrhea or blood in stool.  No URI sxms.  No SOB or CP, other than the discomfort after swallowing.  No neuro sxms other than diffuse aching pains and fatigue.  She reports similar challenges with achiness and fatigue after prior flu vaccines, although current sxms are more than she expected.  She "avoids vaccines when possible" but is concerned about infections, like flu, and generally receives recommended vaccines.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Worsening Left arm pain starting around day 3 after injection.  There was pain at the time of injection that was slightly worse than a usual flu vaccine.  The pain is a constant ache 8/10 at rest, only 2/10 when active.  It has a neuropathic characteristic in that there is no soreness or tenderness at the site anymore; it does not hurt more when I press on the site; it hurts constantly without provocation; ice does not make it better; heat makes it much worse.  It is very difficult to sit at a desk and do work; the pain intensifies the longer I sit.  It is much less intense when I am active and moving the arm.   It is not getting any better with time, in fact, it seems to be getting worse.  I am now almost 6 weeks after the injection.  I do not plan to get the second, booster vaccine since this seems worse than having the shingles.
OTHER_MEDS: Atorvastatin 10mg every day Protonix 40mg every day

The patient reported that her arm felt fine after her shot until around bedtime last evening, when it got so sore and painful that she could not lift it at all; she said she could only move her hand a little.  She took an Aleve and went to bed.  When she got up this morning it was still very painful and she could not lift it.  She took another Aleve but it did not help.  I asked if it was red or swollen and she stated she could not even take her arm out of her blouse to look.  I contacted her primary care physician, who advised that she go to the walk-in clinic.  The patient did so, and I talked to her after.  She said the doctor told her there was a little swelling but no redness, and an X-ray of her shoulder showed nothing that would have been caused by the shot.  The doctor concluded it was a bad reaction to the shot.  She was given 2 Tylenol and advised to use cold compresses to help with the discomfort.  If she has any other issues she is to follow up with her primary care physician.

area of the inflammation was about 3 inch by 5 inch; Site of the injection was raised and about 5 mm in diameter.; The inflammation was quite pink; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site inflammation in a 67-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included systemic lupus erythematosus.   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced injection site inflammation, injection site swelling and injection site erythema. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site inflammation, injection site swelling and injection site erythema were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site inflammation, injection site swelling and injection site erythema to be related to Shingrix.   Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter was the patient's husband. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had lupus. The reporter described the reaction as, site of the injection was raised and about 5 mm in diameter. The area of the inflammation was about 3 inch by 5 inch and the inflammation was quite pink. Again, the reporter asked to send a photo of patient's reaction if anyone who would like to see it at any time. The patient's PA (physician assistant) recommended that, she should not get a 2nd shot. The reporter wondered how much protection could protect the patient. The reporter asked about the efficacy of receiving just one Shingrix vaccine injection instead of two shots to which the GlaxoSmithKline representative replied that, during clinical trials, evaluation of the efficacy of Shingrix started 1 month after the 2nd dose, therefore, the efficacy of the vaccine is unknown if the second dose is not received.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Arterial bleed into her deltoid muscle that was then festering; High dose of flu vaccine administered; Provider who administered the vaccine injected it into her artery; Arterial bleed into her deltoid muscle that was then festering; This is a spontaneous case, reported by other non-health professional to agency[reference number: SEQ19-07068] and initially received on 27-Nov-2019, concerning an 83-year-old, female patient.  The patient's medical history included rheumatoid arthritis, hypertension and diabetes. The patient was taking unspecified concomitant medications, however, the brand names were not provided.  On 05-Nov-2019, the patient was administered unspecified Flu vaccine [Influenza vaccine, batch number: 260397, route of administration: into the artery, anatomical location: right arm, dose reported as 'high' and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Inappropriate route of vaccination' and 'Inappropriate dose of vaccine administered') for influenza prophylaxis.  On 06-Nov-2019, one day after vaccination, the patient experienced slight soreness.   On an unspecified date in Nov-2019, reported as a week later, the patient had significant pain in her entire right arm.  On 22-Nov-2019, the patient was still experiencing severe pain, and she lost most of the ability to use her arm.  On 24-Nov-2019, the patient was taken to the emergency room (ER) due to severe edema, heat, hardness of her upper arm along with bruising from her shoulder to elbow. In the hospital it was noted that the vaccine was injected into patient's artery, causing arterial bleeding into the deltoid muscle that festered until the pain became unbearable. The patient started treatment with unspecified pain killers and antibiotic, and her blood thinners were stopped for a week. The patient was not hospitalised.   At the time of initial reporting, the patient had not recovered form the events. It was reported that the patient continued to have no use of right arm, and she still had heat, swelling and bruising from shoulder to arm, and was unable to use her cane.   The event of 'arterial bleeding' was assessed as serious (medically significant) per company.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  Company Comment: The patient experienced arterial haemorrhage and infection (reported as arterial bleed into her deltoid muscle that was then festering) after incorrect route and dose of product unspecified Flu vaccine administration. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of diabetes may have contributed to events. No concomitant medications were provided. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as possibly related.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced arterial haemorrhage and infection (reported as arterial bleed into her deltoid muscle that was then festering) after incorrect route and dose of product unspecified Flu vaccine administration. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of diabetes may have contributed to events. No concomitant medications were provided. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as possibly related.

permanent scarring; balance and breathing problems; balance and breathing problems; a rash and painful shingles on her neck and face; Information has been received from a lawyer concerning a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of an unknown age. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition and has suffered economic losses due to her inability to work. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's conduct, the patient have suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the shot and went home. My arm got a little sore that evening. The next day I got a large hard knot at the injection site. It was so big I showed my daughter who is a nurse. I was having more pain in the arm starting the next day. It was the weekend as I had my shot on a Friday so I didn't call anyone until the next week. I sent my primary care Dr a note stating I was having pain still a week later. They said to give it more time. I also reported the pain and knot to the Clinic number.. I continued with the pain for awhile thinking it would just take time to go away. But it hasn't.  So I went in to see my PCP and she examined me and suggested ice and exercises pushing against the wall. After several weeks it didn't feel improved at all. So she did an X-ray and that only showed the bone so she sent me for an MRI. I'm waiting for the results done 2 days ago.  I've lost my range of motion. It's difficult to drive and turn the wheel on the left.  I can't sleep on my left side. I can't dry my back after a shower or fasten my bra in the back. I can't dry my hair easily lifting my arms up and dressing myself with clothes going over my head is difficult. It has changed my life unfortunately.
LAB_DATA: X-ray at PCP office Nov 2019 MRI done at Diagnostic Imaging Dec 3rd 2019
OTHER_MEDS: Toprol  Rosavastatin Synthroid Methenamine Hipp a Aspirin 81 mg.    COQ10.  Vitamin C

Child left the office right after vaccination and went to Starbucks with his parents.  While there, approximately 30 min after vaccination, he developed a bad coughing spell and turned red.  Following that he had audible wheezing.  Parents reported he had hives vs. facial flushing.  No medications were given.  He returned to the office and was seen by me approximately 1 hour after vaccination.  At that time he had no rash or wheezing and was no longer coughing.   He was then well until he developed persistent wheezing on 11/28/19.  He was seen by another doctor in our practice on 11/29/19 and was treated with albuterol and prednisolone.  Symptoms and exam had improved on follow-up on 11/30/2019.
ALLERGIES: egg, wheat, peanut, tree nut, milk, sesame  (rashes and hives, no history of anaphylaxis)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: - Day after shot: headache. Advil relieved it. (Also  had  sore throat and hoarse voice beginning a few hours after shot, but probably unrelated; had slight throat itch day prior.) - 48 hours after shot: headache. Advil relieved it. RASH on chest, stomach and back.  Took 2 Benadryl. Rash was gone the next morning.  (Still have sore throat and cough.) - NOTE:  I had this same reaction to the first dose of Shingles Shot that I had in early Sept. 2019.
CUR_ILL: slight throat itch day prior to vaccine. After vaccine - major soar throat and hoarse voice that afternoon, and still 3 days later.
PRIOR_VAX: 1st Shingles vaccine - early Sept. 2019 - same reaction.
ALLERGIES: Had reaction to either local anesthetic or epi twice:  during dental surgery and also when having a cyst removed from my back.  Blood pressure dropped, shaking, cold (during dental), hot/sweating (during dermatologist).

acute hypoxemic respiratory failure; hypeoxemic; multifocal pneumonia; COPD exacerbation; shingles.; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. The patient's medical history, concurrent condition and concomitant medication were not reported.      On or around 12-JAN-2017 the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster).        Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered severe cough and shortness of breath. The patient was hospitalized and diagnosed with acute hypoxemic respiratory failure, multifocal pneumonia and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) exacerbation. Shortly after hospitalization, the patient suffered from a severe rash on her chest and right flank. The patient was diagnosed with shingles. As a direct and proximate result of defective zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to the vaccination. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries (disability) Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The outcome of the events was not resolved. The causality assessment was related. The reporter considered the events to be disabling.   Upon internal review, acute hypoxemic respiratory failure and multifocal pneumonia were determined to be medically significant.  Additional information has been requested.

Extreme pain at the injection site; Difficulty raising arm  and lifting objects.; Sirva; Vaccine administered at inappropriate site; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site pain in a 26-year-old female patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Quebec (FluLaval Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season) (batch number E975Y, expiry date 25th June 2019) for prophylaxis.   On 17th October 2019, the patient received FluLaval Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season. On 17th October 2019, less than a day after receiving FluLaval Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season, the patient experienced injection site pain, injected limb mobility decreased, shoulder injury related to vaccine administration and vaccine administered at inappropriate site. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site pain, injected limb mobility decreased and vaccine administered at inappropriate site were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the shoulder injury related to vaccine administration was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site pain, injected limb mobility decreased and shoulder injury related to vaccine administration to be related to FluLaval Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient reported extreme pain at the injection site which remain till the time of reporting. The patient has difficulty raising his arm and lifting objects. The patient was administered the vaccine the same day and was given by the same nurse. The reporter suspects the vaccine was administered too high on the deltoid resulting in symptoms that occur with sirva, that was the shoulder injury which was related to vaccine administration. The reporter consented to follow up. This case was one of the 9 case reported by the same reporter.

Flu-like symptoms; Nasal drip caused her to cough a lot; Felt so poorly; Headache; Nasal drip, including a runny nose and post-nasal drip; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of influenza-like symptoms in a 68-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 16th October 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). In October 2019, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced cough and feeling unwell. On 17th October 2019, the patient experienced influenza-like symptoms, headache and runny nose. On 19th October 2019, the outcome of the influenza-like symptoms was recovered/resolved. On 21st November 2019, the outcome of the feeling unwell was recovering/resolving. On an unknown date, the outcome of the headache, runny nose and cough were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the influenza-like symptoms, headache, runny nose, cough and feeling unwell to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix intramuscularly. On 17th October 2019, 1 day after vaccination with Shingrix, the patient experienced flu-like symptoms,  headache and nasal drip, including a runny nose and post-nasal drip, that lasted for 5-6 weeks.  The nasal drip caused her to cough a lot as well.  On 21st November 2019, the patient started feeling better. She saw her doctor for the headache and nasal drip and had an MRI done, but nothing showed on the scan.  She never got sick and was concerned about how she felt so poorly for so long. The reporter consented to follow-up.      Lab Comments: On an unknown date, in 2019, the patient had an MRI done.

Subchorionic hematoma; Anemia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 27-Nov-2019, concerning a 23-year-old, female pregnant subject of body weight: 114 lbs, height: 65 inches and body mass index (BMI): 19 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's current condition was not provided. The subject's concomitant medication included Prenatal vitamin (mineral nos, vitamin nos) for pregnancy.  The subject's obstetrical history noted that subject had two previous pregnancies with two full term live births. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 22-Jan-2019. The subject's estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were 29-Oct-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The father was 24-year old.  On 12-Mar-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 16-May, the subject underwent ultrasound and mother's serum alpha fetoprotein (MSAFP) / serum markers and no MCM was noted.  On 26-May-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 03-Jun-2019, the subject underwent spinal muscular atrophy and cystic fibrosis mutation analysis and no MCM was noted.  On 19-Sep-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 04-Oct-2019, at gestational age at 36 weeks, the subject was administered with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, batch number: 261218, dose: 0.5 ml, anatomical location, route of administration and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.  On the same day, the subject underwent ultrasound and no MCM was noted.  On 07-Oct-2019, three days after vaccination, the patient developed anaemia and was treated with ferrous sulfate, 325 mg, twice a day (BID), orally (from 07-Oct-2019 to 22-Oct-2019).  On an unspecified date, after an unknown amount of time after vaccination, the patient developed subchorionic hematoma, but the details were not specified.  At gestational age of 39 weeks, the mother vaginally delivered live birth, female neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 3175 g, her head circumference was 34.3 cm and length was 48.9 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). There was no major congenital malformation identified at birth. At the time of delivery, no pregnancy complications were reported.  The outcome of the event anaemia was recovered, on 22-Oct-2019.  At the time of this report, the outcome of event subchorionic hematoma was not reported.  The event of subchorionic hematoma was assessed as serious due to criterion of medical significance per company.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIV.  This case is linked to baby case 201907053.  Company Comment: The subject experienced subchorionic haematoma and anaemia after vaccination with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at 36 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. Pregnant state may provide alternative aetiology for the events. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events subchorionic haematoma and anaemia is assessed as unlikely related.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced subchorionic haematoma and anaemia after vaccination with the suspect product Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Uncontrollable shivering for 2 hours, starting about 12 hours after injection.  Body, mainly hands and legs, where cold. Headache, muscle aches everywhere. Injection site very painful and developed a swelling which subsided after 24 hours, but still very tender and difficult to move.

Note I sent to Dr. about a week after:  "From: Patient  Sent: 9/28/2019 4:04 PM  To: MD Subject: RE: Non-Urgent Medical Question  Received a flu shot little more than a week ago. Initially had sore shoulder in general and more acutely in my shoulder joint toward the front. It is painful to lift my arm last 90. It is painful to put on a coat ( swinging to the rear motion). Buckling seat belt motion is painful. I'm concerned something isn't right. The injection felt "bubbly" toward the end."  The shot didn't feel right. The Pharmacist did not pinch the muscle and the shot felt high in the arm. At the end of the injection before he removed the needle I felt a "burst, or bubbling" sensation in my shoulder joint immediately followed by the pain that I still have today. I've had several flu shots in the past and I'm familiar with the soreness that comes on after the shot and lingers for about a day. I had that pain as well, but it came and went like it usually does.  I always bleed after an injection and there was no blood this time.  Wife commented about how high the bandaid was on my shoulder. Do not remember seeing a bruise.  Today, December 6th, 2019, I am still experiencing pain. Pain lifting or lowering the weight of a milk jug or more past horizontal. Pushing down to lift my weight. Cross body motions like coats or robes. Sometimes feels like the arm is weaker, like I cannot lift my coat to swing it on.   The pain feels sharp, comes on quick and goes away quick. Though sometimes if I lift an object that causes the pain, it will be sustained.
LAB_DATA: Had a well check up with my Doctor and described the pain and when it started. She told me she's seen one other patient with this in the past and that it took a very long time to get better. She indicated the injection is the likely cause. We discussed the possibility that the injection was too deep and was forced into the joint rather than staying in the muscle.   She suggested Advil for pain and that I could do PT, but that it doesn't seem to help in this situation.

After the checkup, she told us that baby is good in growth. Vaccination done on 10-23-2019 at 11.30 AM EST. Attached vaccination card in this email. Please check.  On the same day around 3 pm, kid was sleeping and suddenly we heard some grunting sounds.  We checked baby and observed that baby eyes were rolling and unconscious and unable to breathe.  We tried to wake him up but he didn't wake up. Immediately, we understand the seriousness and called 911. Ambulance came in less than five minutes and they pump the air for breathing problem and they took the baby to hospital. They helped him breathing, given IV fluids, removed urine using catheter, and some first-aid process. Also taken chest x-ray and CT SCAN.  They said that X-ray and CT-scan were good. Baby opened eyes, crying a lot and my wife feed him ( breast feeding). On the same day around 7 PM, Pediatrician sent the baby to  hospital for observation.  Baby reached Hospital around 8 PM.   Sr.physician Told me that it may be Hypoxia/seizures due to low level Oxygen in blood and baby is in life & death situation.   At this time, the baby is almost normal, opening eyes and recognizing us and crying for pain ( May be pain in hand - intravenous  drip) They Started Brain ECG  and started giving treatment for seizures. Baby was not sleeping and crying the complete night.  (They started giving medicine for stopping seizures, antibiotics, sodium carbonate, liquids and IV fluids.)  Thursday 10-24-2019: My son was crying throughout night. He got a fever 102c and in mid night around 2.30 AM and 5.30 AM, he just moved his legs, hands, and head. Doctors said that this may be seizures as they are rhythmic movement. They took him to MRI scan and spinal tap( extract liquid from spinal) test. They said that MRI and spinal tap test looks good. Evening, Baby got the flu and fever went up to 104. Baby eyes were swollen and can't open.  Baby was crying through out night. They continue the seizure medicines and also given Tamiflu, tylenol, antibiotics etc.  Friday 10-25-2019: They said the baby had a series of seizures on Thursday night and not stopping. They are using Keppra along with some other medicine for seizures. Also Tamiflu, antibiotics, sodium bicarbonate , and tylenol gave him. He went to deep sleep due to high Seizures medicine dose. Doctors put the baby on ventilator. Also, inserted pipe to stomach through the nose for feeding. No movement.. no crying...  Saturday 10-26-2019: Doctors told us that seizures controlled a little bit but the brain is generating abnormal waves.  Now they reduced seizures dose. But again seizures come back. Continued same medicine till evening. Doctors told us that baby is in very critical condition.  Sunday 10-27-2019: They did MRI again and say that brain damaged and can't irreversible. Now, they have given (pentabola-  something, not sure), to put him on comma and trying to save my baby. Doctors stitched(for intravenous  drip) on his groin and wrist.  They used catheter to remove urine from bladder. And now they say it's a five percent chance of living and if he lives, he will have different health issues in the future. At 9.30 Pm, nurses and doctors treating my son continuously till 12.30 AM ( Monday)  Monday 10-28-2019: 12.30 AM :Doctor told us that brain dead and kidneys also failed, heart also will stop in a couple of hours.  They stopped treatment. We were in deep sad and crying. Baby's heart beat is reducing slowly. Around 11.40 AM, heart beating also stopped.  My son had very painful, dreadful, unbearable treatment but he is not alive. We are crying from the incident (10-23-2019).  we had very terrible days and sleepless crying nights.   Before Incident: Baby was born. He was a full term 40-week baby and no health issues.  First Vaccination on 07-05-2019. (Baby cried a lot about 20 to 30 mints. After that, the baby was normal. We thought that the baby was crying due to pain in thighs. No fever, no other issues.)  Baby was in this country till 07-11-2019.  Baby went to parents home country with parents on 07-11-2019 and returned this country on 10-20-2019. When baby was in parents home country, no health issues except 1. mild fever - fever about 100c ( on 09-10-2019) - gave Tylenol for 2 times in a day and the baby was fine. 2. Constipation problem for 3 days (on 09-22-2019) - Consulted Pediatrician and baby was fine the next day.   I have requested medical reports and waiting for them from hospital. Once, I recieved them, I will submit.
CUR_ILL: 1. mild fever - fever about 100 centigrade ( on 09-10-2019) - gave Tylenol for 2 times in a day and the baby was fine. 2. Constipation problem for 3 days (on 09-22-2019) - Consulted Pediatrician and baby was fine in next day.

I spent the first 24 years of my life totally healthy! I lived a very active,  healthy and full life with my husband and 2 dogs.  My health started to decline after my first and second gardasil vaccination but I never questioned that the vaccination caused my problems, I just thought it was a coincidence that the time lines matched up.  I developed Celiac Disease, Hashimotos Disease, severe stomach problems, motility issues, heart burn, anxiety, and neurological problems like neuropathy and parethesia.  After my third and final vaccination I woke up the next morning and had a severe profound fatigue that left me bed bound.  That fatigue never went away.  This time I new it was indeed the vaccination. It has been almost 1.5 years since my last vaccination and my life is completely ruined.  I quit my job, quit school, and spend 90% of my time in bed too tired to even watch TV.  My immune system has been completely ruined and now I have several other bacterial and viral infections I live with.  The gardasil vaccination ruined my, I would give anything to go back in time and undo it.  I think it is also worth noting that when I was 17 years old I had the first and second round of the gardasil vaccination, but I never went back to receive the third.  Then, 7 years later I was told I should restart and get all 3 vaccinations in the 6 months timeline that is recommended.  So I have actually had 5 gardasil vaccinations.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests (lots), Enoscopies, colonoscopy, gastric emptying study, barium swallow test.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Minor  "frozen shoulder" like symptoms in my surgically repaired left shoulder. Significantly limited range of motion (at the worst only about 20 degrees of movement) and joint pain (6/10 left shoulder). Symptoms persisted for approximately 10 days with improvement each day following onset. I used physical therapy exercises previously used in should rehabilitation. I was able to find some anecdotal evidence for this sort of reaction. Had problems persisted longer or gotten worse I would have sought medical treatment. I wanted to add my report as collateral information for possible future research into this sort of reaction.
OTHER_MEDS: 20 mg Adderall XR, 10 mg Adderall IR, 300 mg Bupropion, 10 mg Zyrtec

Tuesday evening around 7 pm I received Afluria Qiv Flu vaccine within 15 minutes of receiving the shot I felt shortness of breath, my throat began to swell and my chest started to tighten. I called the pharmacist and spoke with him, he told me I might be able to treat at home but I should go in if I get worse, I then called the nurse advice line who told me I can treat at home with Benadryl. During this phone call my chest and neck broke out in hives, every step I took felt heavy, I felt dizzy, I had diarrhea, my arm started to swell, get hives and was hot to touch. My hands and arms started to feel tingly like pins and needles feeling. I had a friend rush me to the ER where and EKG, blood work and chest x-ray were done. I was given a very high dose of Benadryl through my IV which made the swelling in my throat go down but made me throw up after I sat up to get my x-ray, I was then given decadron and fluids, about half way through that I felt the tightness in my chest ease up however, I was still having some issues catching my breath, the x-ray showed I had a very high amount of air in my stomach which was swollen. before I was released I threw up and had my second bout of diarrhea. I was unable to go to work the next 3 day due to extreme exhaustion, feeling faint, headaches, tingly feeling in my hands, having trouble catching my breath, nausea and vomiting, I still had a rash on my chest and would become out of breath walking to the next room. My throat would feel like it was swelling and I took some Benadryl to help. Today (11/24) is the first day I am starting to feel not as weak. I have not vomited, felt faint, I feel like the hives on my chest are almost gone.
LAB_DATA: Blood work 19-NOV-2019, ABS Basophils; ABS Monocytes 0.8x10(3)/mcL Higher Than Normal APTT 27.9 Sec Lower Than Norm
OTHER_MEDS: HYDROQUIN 4% TOP CREAM; Tylenol & Motrin as needed.
ALLERGIES: Penicillin, Sulfa antibiotics, Amoxicillin, Azithromycin, Neosporin

Took my 9 year old, daughter to pharmacy on Friday 12/06/2019 at 4:55 p.m. to get her annual flu shot.  At 5:17 p.m. I received a phone call from the pharmacist who explained that she accidently gave my daughter the Shingrix vaccination by mistake and was told that this shot was not intended for children and was designed for adults 50 year and older. We immediately called poison control where staff explained to us the possible side effects and to monitor her for the next 48 hours to make sure she doesn't have any major outbreaks or major fever spikes.    Friday evening patient ran a fever most of the evening which we were able to keep her comfortable w/ childrens ibuprofen.  She could barely lift her arm and the injection point on her left arm could not be touched without severe pain.  Arm was swollen at the point of injection and was very red.  Saturday, patient continued to run a fever and slept most of the day which was not like her at all.  She experienced the same level of pain in the arm and functionality was limited.  We again comforted her w/ childrens ibuprofen.  Swelling in the arm had gone down but had splotches of red around the point of injection about the size of the palm of her hand. Sunday evening, patient's fever began to calm down and she started to gain more mobility in her arm with less pain to the touch.  We monitored the red splotches to ensure they remained localized which they did. Monday morning, no fever and she has started to gain what appears to be full functionality in her arm.  Arm still a little red and splotches have not spread as of today.
