patient may have received a portion or a small bit of the vaccine/no AE; After I squirted it in to him, i checked the needle and it was on tightly/no AE; there was a hole near the hub and that is what caused the leak.The syringe and needle/no AE; Initial information received on 14-Oct-2019 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a pharmacist.  This case involves a 89 years old male patient who received partial dose of vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV].  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided. At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing Immunodeficiency and Leukaemia.  Concomitant medications included PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE POLYSACCH 23V (PNEUMOVAX 23) for Immunisation.  On 14-Oct-2019, the patient received a single 0.5 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE lot QFAA1912 via unknown route in unknown administration site.  It was of actual medication error due to Vaccine underdose and Exposure via skin contact. It was also a case of Product quality issue. The syringe needle was injected into the patient and then when pharmacist pushed the plunger, the vaccine liquid squirted out from the hub to where it narrows down- the gap between the hub and the syringe- it squirted out there between the glass and the hub of the syringe. The liquid fell out on the chair. The pharmacist stated "it felt like it might not be sterile. There was a hole. The liquid vaccine looked clear and was not cloudy. After pharmacist squirted it in to him, pharmacist checked the needle and it was on tightly. It is not an issue with the needle, but there appears that there was a hole near the hub and that is what caused the leak. The syringe and needle are in the sharps container and are not available for return. The patient may have received a portion or a small bit of the vaccine. The pharmacist gave the patient another dose of the Flublok Quad vaccine of the same lot as the one that leaked. The second syringe was fine. The patient is already immunocompromised. He has leukemia. The pharmacist stated that she is concerned that the vaccine that she gave was not sterile and worries about what could happen as a result to this immunocompromised patient.  It was unknown whether any adverse event was noted or not.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Of course arm pain (it was in my left (non-dominant) arm in which I sometimes have discomfort from nerve impingement at my neck & for which I take gabapentin. The pharmacist helpfully instructed me to gently move arm to avoid stiffening. Also I took some Advil before the shot, and that helped, too. The movement and the Advil  helped, and everyone taking this vaccine should be instructed to do so.  The more alarming symptoms were a kind of labored breathing. It's true I have some emphysema and continue to smoke! but this was different. I did feel increased weakness. I have had dizziness sporadically for a year, maybe two  years, and I'm not sure if this vaccine increased or exacerbated that. I felt some general chest  pressure as well as some panic, both of which I sometimes do anyway, and again, I feel the vaccine may have worsened these. I felt a little bit of sweating & chills. My heart beat is usually pretty slow (49, 62 - it varies) but these first several hours after the vaccine it was up to about 72 bpm and not worrisome to me. After about 6 hours or so these symptoms lessened, and I calmed down more as well. I want to mention them because some of my symptoms were on the "Call 911 if this happens" list and I didn't quite know what to do.  (I had an "innocent murmur" at one time in my life and I'm not sure if this is gone, or turned into a calcified aortic vale.)
LAB_DATA: I took my temperature and I think it wasn't more than 100 degrees (I have about 5 thermometers, probably all unreliable).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Influenza vaccine given instead of pneumococcal vaccine at 2 months old.

My arm hurt immediately after getting the flu shot. But I didn't think anything right away as this is typical. The next day it was still bad and didn't go away. It hurt near the shoulder, a sharp pain when I would move  my arm in most directions. Simple things like releasing the parking brake in the car by my knee, pulling a blanket over me in bed. Lifting light things. Opening a door. Everything. I rested it a few days to little but not much improvement. Then things around it started hurting because I wasn't using it and had it glued to my side. My back started freezing up. I was able to treat my back and the things around it with 2 visits to massage therapist specializing in fixing problems. But the shoulder never improved. Still sharp pain from most day to day arm activities with no improvemnt and increasing worry. I finally started in physical therapy after 5 weeks (10/25/19)and I started improving immediately from the strengthening and movement exercises he gave me. These were exercises for shoulder impingement. Bursitis may also describe what I have. I have made consistent progress but it has been a long process. It has been 6 weeks of twice daily physical therapy exercises and icing at home (with 3 PT visits to monitor and increase exercises 10/25, 11/7, 11/22) and now I am able to use my arm more. I still get twinges from most movements and pain (much less than before) from various movements and still have only limited weight-bearing capacity but I continue to do the exercises and go to PT.  Both the doctor and physical therapist asked extensively about other possible causes when I indicated it was due to a flu shot. I said there was no hurt or trauma event and then I've had zero history of shoulder issues and it happens immediately following the flu shot It seems to fit SIRVA shoulder injury related to vaccine administration. My weight and smaller arm muscle mass seem to fit descriptions where the injection can go in too deep and hit the Bursa sack or something else.
LAB_DATA: Was checked by an orthopedist and had xray on 10/16/19.  He said it was all clear in terms of no infection.

her arm was swollen and red red with a lump the size of a golf ball, but not at the site of the injection, rather closer to the elbow region on the inner part of her right arm, about 4 inches below where the shot was given; her arm was swollen and red red with a lump the size of a golf ball, but not at the site of the injection, rather closer to the elbow region on the inner part of her right arm, about 4 inches below where the shot was given; she could hardly move her arm; her arm was swollen and red red with a lump the size of a golf ball, but not at the site of the injection, rather closer to the elbow region on the inner part of her right arm, about 4 inches below where the shot was given; muscle was swollen and hard; that she had difficulty sleeping on that side; her arm began to hurt in the eve; This spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist and a 75-year-old female patient referring to herself. On 22-NOV-2019, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23), intramuscularly in the right arm, lot # S026366, expiration date reported as September 2019 but upon internal review established as 17-SEP-2019 (dose was not reported) for prophylaxis. The pharmacist reported that on 23-NOV-2019, the patient's arm was swollen and red with a lump the size of a golf ball, but not at the site of the injection, rather closer to the elbow region on the inner part of her right arm, about 4 inches below where the shot was given. The patient could hardly move her arm. The outcome of the lump on vaccinated arm was reported as not recovered/not resolved. The outcome of difficulty sleeping, muscle hardness and arm pain was unknown. SYMPTOM_TEXT: the patient had a temperature of 101 / she no longer has a fever; flu-like symptoms; stiff neck; whole body itching and pain; whole body itching and pain/whole body aches; inflammation and redness of the whole deltoid starting right away after the patient received the vaccination and lasting for two weeks; inflammation and redness of the whole deltoid starting right away after the patient received the vaccination and lasting for two weeks; the area where she received the vaccination is very itchy/itching continued at the site of injection; This spontaneous report has been received from a pharmacist referring to a 57 year old female patient. No information was provided regarding the patient�s medical history, concurrent conditions, drug and allergy history or concomitant medications.   On 11-NOV-2019, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) intramuscularly (strength, dose and frequency were not provided) lot # R018731, expiration date 27-FEB-2020 for prophylaxis.    The reporter stated that, on 11-NOV-2019, right away after the patient received the vaccination, she experienced whole body itching (pruritus) and pain, inflammation (vaccination site inflammation) and redness (vaccination site erythema) of the whole deltoid. On 12-NOV-2019, the patient had a temperature of 101 (units not provided)(pirexia), flu-like symptoms (influenza like illness), stiff neck (musculoskeletal stiffness) and whole body aches (pain). On an unspecified date in November 2019, the whole body itching went away but continued at the site of the injection (vaccination site pruritus). On 30-NOV-2019, the patient reported to the pharmacist that she went to the doctor because the area where she received the vaccination was very itchy. The doctor prescribed topical diphenhydramine (BENADRYL) which helped a little bit. As of 30-NOV-2019, the patient's deltoid was no longer inflamed, red and sore. She no longer had a fever, flu-like symptoms, stiff neck and whole body aches. The whole body itching had resolved but continued at the site of the injection. At the reporting time, the causal relationship between the aforementioned events and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) was not reported. The reporter considered the events to be medically significant.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: New employee presented to Employee Health Office for egg-free flu shot.  She endorsed hx. of prior vaccine reactions, did not have documentation.  She received Flublok injection at ~1000 am.  We asked her to stay in office for few minutes of observation.  ~ 10 min. after injection, she began to c/o her tongue feeling numb along side.  She was lucid, slid down in the chair and then said she needed to lay down.  We helped her to the floor.  She remained responsive but did have short, few seconds of non-responsiveness, appeared to go limp, but never stopped breathing.  We checked her VS.  BP was elevated, HR wnl, O2 sat 100%.  She was responsive & c/o nausea.  She did not vomit.  We attempted to administer epinephrine, first into her left deltoid, then into her left anterior thigh.  The injection didn't appear to function appropriately and much of the medication spilled onto her clothing and floor.  We called a Campus Response for assistance and then I decided we should call a Code to access more resources. The Code Team arrived and I assisted putting her on a backboard and onto gurney.  She was shaking so we applied warm blankets.  Another nurse accompanied her to the ED with a copy of the VS we had taken.  The patient never lost consciousness.  She c/o pain in her thigh where epi injection had been attempted.
OTHER_MEDS: Tirosint (Thyroid) 75 mg - 1X per day, Midodrine 2.5mg - 3X per day to increase BP, Cholestyramine Powder 3X per day, taking temporarily as "off label" for mold poisoning .
CUR_ILL: Caregiver lists multiple symptoms on her Employee Health History related to prolonged toxic mold exposure. Neurological: numbness, tingling, headaches, weakness, drowsiness, coordination.
HISTORY: As stated above re: mold exposure.
PRIOR_VAX: Tetanus as a child.  Does not recall symptoms.
ALLERGIES: Penicillin, Pertussis, Tetanus, Synthroid , Armour, Nexium, Bactrim

I went to the doctor because I thought I had strep throat. A culture was taken and it was confirmed I had strep throat. The nurse suggested I get the Tetanus shot as it had been a long time since I had one. I said sure, not knowing it was multiple shots in one AND you are NEVER supposed to give a shot when someone is sick! I didn't know this information at the time of the shot. Immediately after the shot I felt hot and sweaty and sick. I asked to use the restroom and barely made it there. I fainted in the restroom. After I woke up I yelled for the nurse to come and help me. She walked me back to the room where I was given the shot. The doctor came back in and placed cold presses on my body to help me. After about 30 minutes I was able to stand up and walk out. I've not felt the same since that Tdap shot that day! My memory has been horrible since that day, I get dizzy very easily and constant headaches. I've had to do acupuncture and chiropractic care to help heal myself from the Tdap shot.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to  Codeine. Intolerance to dairy products.

Atrophy in the left thigh overlying the injection site.  Mother states she noticed this when patient was 10 months old.  Clinically I appreciated the changes when he came in for a flu vaccine in October 2019.   Initially I did not believe the changes were related to vaccines.  In November, when I saw patient for his 12-month Well Check, I began considering the possibility of atrophy of the subcutaneous fatty tissue.  I referred him to pediatric dermatology for further evaluation.   Diagnosis from Dr. (pediatric dermatologist) is not certain, possibilities include lipoatrophy secondary to immunization.  Presumably since mother reports noticing these changes by 10 months old, the most recent injection on the affected thigh would be the Pediarix dose given on May 8, 2019.  Dr. states she has seen this adverse reaction from steroid injections, but never seen it secondary to immunizations.   Other possible causes of the skin changes on the left thigh include morphea and anetoderma (per Dr.'s note).  Unknown if this will cause permanent damage or disability yet.
HISTORY: none other than papular urticaria from July through September 2019

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt was fine after receiving both immunizations. After immunizations were complete, he stood at the counter waiting for me to make copies of the immunization forms for school. While standing at the counter, he passed out and fell to the ground. Another patient in the waiting area said it looked like he was seizing. Seconds later, I was notified he passed out and was on the ground, so I ran to grab my emergency bag and out to the waiting room. He was already talking and saying he was fine. I had pulled out an Epi-Pen in case I needed to administer, and he declined the need for administering it. I asked how he was feeling and he stated he felt fine, but wanted to continue to lay on the floor, just in case. I did grab him some water. 911 was called but the patient declined the need for them to come. Our store manager sat with him in the waiting area for another 15 minutes to make sure he was fine. The patient left on his own, walking, just fine.

This literature marketed report has been received from authors of a published article, referring to a previously healthy 14-year-old boy presented with a 2-day history of malaise, anorexia, and a painful, pruritic rash and a 1-day history of severe headache. Physical examination revealed more than 70 papulovesicular lesions over the lateral aspect of his left thigh in an L1 to L2 dermatomal distribution, photophobia, and meningismus without focal neurologic deficits or altered mental status. The patient had no recent varicella-zoster virus (VZV) exposure and had received 2 varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (manufacturer unknown) (dose, route, lot # and expiration date unknown) at 1 and 4 years of age.  Laboratory studies revealed normal peripheral blood white blood cell (WBC) and platelet counts, liver transaminases, and C-reactive protein level. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) had a Gram-stain result negative for organisms, glucose of 60 mg/dL, protein of 64 mg/dL, red blood cell count of 268/cubic millimetre, and WBC count of 140/cubic millimetre with 88% lymphocytes and 10% monocytes. CSF and a scraping of a vesicular lesion resulted positive for VZV by polymerase chain reaction (PCR); virus from both specimens genotyped as vOka. VZV seroconversion was confirmed, and CSF tested negative for VZV IgG. The patient was human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) negative with normal numbers and percentages of T- and B-cell subsets. He was treated for 7 days with intravenous (IV) acyclovir. Pain resolved, and no new lesions developed after 3 days of treatment; headache, photophobia, and meningismus resolved after 5 days; neurologic examination was normal at discharge. Malaise resolved 2 weeks later. The authors considered meningitis to be related to varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown).  Upon internal review, meningitis was determined to be medically significant.  A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.  This is one of two reports received from the same literature.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-1912USA005082:

SYMPTOM_TEXT: anaphylaxis; restless; red skin; swelling; nausea; fever; high blood pressure; Heart racing; tachycardia; feeling bad; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of anaphylaxis in a 78-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 23rd October 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 23rd October 2019, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced anaphylaxis (serious criteria GSK medically significant), restlessness, skin red, swelling, nausea, fever, blood pressure high, heart racing, tachycardia and feeling bad. The patient was treated with acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) and metoprolol tartrate (Lopressor). On an unknown date, the outcome of the anaphylaxis, restlessness, skin red, swelling, nausea, fever and blood pressure high were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the heart racing, tachycardia and feeling bad were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the anaphylaxis, restlessness, skin red, swelling, nausea, fever, blood pressure high, heart racing, tachycardia and feeling bad to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows:  By the evening of vaccination, she was feeling very restless.  The skin on her head turned bright red and was swollen and she could feel her heart beating like crazy.  The patient's heart was going into tachycardia.  She started getting nauseated and had a fever.  The patient took some Aspirin and slept that night, but she was still feeling bad on 24th October 2019.  The patient finally went to the emergency room around 4 PM and her heart was racing and her blood pressure was very elevated.  She said it was anaphylaxis.  She was given Lopressor IV push and stayed at the emergency room for about 6 hours before going home. The reporter consented to follow up.

Secondary bronchitis and laryngitis; Secondary bronchitis and laryngitis; Paraesthesia; Influeza infection cannot be completely ruled out; Mycoplasma pneumoniae infection; This is a spontaneous case, initially received from other health care professional on 18-Nov-2019, with additional information received on 25-Nov-2019 (being processed together), concerning a 38-year-old, female patient.   The patient's medical history included unspecified flu vaccine with no adverse reaction reported.   The patient's concomitant medications were not provided.   On 06-May-2019, the patient was administered Afluria Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, expiration date: Feb-2020, batch number reported as 49601-02503, route of administration: intramuscular, dose: 0.5 ml and anatomical location: upper right arm as reported] as active immunization against influenza disease (prophylaxis).  On an unspecified date in 2019, at unknown time after vaccination, the patient developed mycoplasma pneumoniae infection.  On 16-Nov-2019 in the morning, six months and ten days after vaccination, the patient returned from a trip with a sore throat and cough. The patient's symptoms worsened as the day progressed and included pyrexia, body aches, nausea, and fatigue. The patient also experienced paraesthesia.   On the same day, six months and ten days after vaccination, the patient started therapy with oseltamivir.  On 18-Nov-2019, in the morning, the patient went to her general practitioner (GP) who confirmed the diagnosis of influenza. The patient's GP took a throat swab. The results showed that influenza A and influenza B were not detected, while mycoplasma pneumonia was detected. It was reported that influenza virus was not detected, and that initial influenza infection cannot be completely ruled out due to a close contact developing influenza 1.5 days after contact with the patient (with no other likely exposure to influenza virus in timeframe for incubation as reported). According by the throat swab, it was also reported that initial influenza infection cannot be confirmed due to lack of detection.   On 21-Nov-2019, five days after the onset, the patient recovered from the event paraesthesia, and the symptoms of pyrexia and body aches were also resolved.   On 22-Nov-2019, the patient developed a secondary bronchitis and laryngitis.  On 25-Nov-2019, the patient started on roxithromycin, at a dose of 150 mg administered two times per day as corrective treatment for the bronchitis and laryngitis.   On 25-Nov-2019, at the evening, the patient started treatment with clarithromycin, at a dose of 500 mg administered two times per day for 7 days and cefuroxime, at the dose of 250 mg two times per day for 5 days.  On 27-Nov-2019, the symptoms of sore throat, nausea and fatigue were resolved.  On 30-Nov-2019, the patient stopped treatment with cefuroxime.  0n 02-Dec-2019, the patient stopped treatment with clarithromycin.  At the time of this report, the patient was recovering from the events of influenza, bronchitis and laryngitis. It was that reported symptom of cough, bronchitis and laryngitis had not fully resolved. The outcome of the event mycoplasma infection was not reported.  The events of mycoplasma infection and influenza were considered serious due to the criterion of medical significance.  The reporter assessed all events to be related to Afluria Quadrivalent, as it was reported that she experienced 'lack of efficacy with Afluria Quad'.   Follow up received by other health care professional on 02-Dec-2019: Details about Afluria Quadrivalent vaccination were provided, test results were provided, updated outcome for the events was provided, new event of mycoplasma pneumoniae infection. Treatment measures were provided. Narrative amended accordingly.  Company Comment: The patient experienced mycoplasma infection, influenza, paraesthesia, bronchitis and laryngitis after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is very unsuggestive due to very long event onset latency, more than 6 months. Throat swab showed that influenza A and influenza B were not detected, while mycoplasma pneumonia was detected. Patent's exposure to infective agents may provide more plausible alternative aetiology. No medical history and concomitant medications were reported. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as unlikely related.; Reporter's Comments: I'm writing to report a case of lack of efficacy with Afluria Quad, for which unfortunately the patient is me.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced mycoplasma infection, influenza, paraesthesia, bronchitis and laryngitis after vaccination with the suspect product Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is very unsuggestive due to very long event onset latency, more than 6 months. Throat swab showed that influenza A and influenza B were not detected, while mycoplasma pneumonia was detected. Patent's exposure to infective agents may provide more plausible alternative aetiology. No medical history and concomitant medications were reported. Considering all the above mentioned, causality between suspect product and the events is assessed as unlikely related.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Low birth weight; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 02-Dec-2019 concerning a female neonatal subject whose mother was 45-year-old pregnant, female subject of body weight: 222 Ibs, height: 65 in and body mass index (BMI) 36.9 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study. The subject's father was 47-year-old.  The subject's mother had five previous pregnancies with two spontaneous abortions and three full term live birth pregnancies with no birth defects. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The subject's mother had no history of offspring with MCM. The subject's mother used half pack of cigarettes per day during pregnancy. The subject's mother did not use alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The mother's current medical condition included deep vein thrombosis. The mother's concomitant medications included enoxaparin and Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), both for deep vein thrombosis, and prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins and minerals) for pregnancy.   The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was on 15-Mar-2019. Estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 15-Dec-2019 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 18-Dec-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 31-May-2019, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound and no MCMs were noted. On the same day, the subject's mother underwent Maternit 21 and increased risk for chromosome 21 was noted.  On 24-Oct-2019, at approximately 31 weeks of gestation, the subject's mother was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD (Flucelvax QIVc) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261226, dose: 0.5 mL, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.   At approximately 37 weeks of gestation, the mother delivered a live female neonate via Caesarean method. The neonate's birth weight was 2211 grams, body length and head circumference were not reported. The reported appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute was 7, at five minutes was 9 and no data was provided at 10 minutes. No MCMs were identified at birth.  At the time of initial reporting, the outcome for the event of low birth weight baby was not reported.  Per company, the event of low birth weight baby was assessed as serious due to criterion of medical significance.   The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Flucelvax QIVc.  This case is linked to case number 201907068 (corresponding mother case).  Company Comment: The female neonatal subject was delivered as low birth weight baby after foetal exposure during pregnancy (at approximately 31 weeks of gestation) with the suspect product Flucelvax QIV. Chronology is plausible. Mother's medical history of cigarette smoking may provide more plausible alternative aetiology for the event. Mother's concomitant medications, enoxaparin and Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), and obesity body mass index (36.9) may have also contributed to development of the event in significant way. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. For the event low birth weight baby, causal role of the suspect product cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as unlikely related.; Sender's Comments: The female neonatal subject was delivered as low birth weight baby after foetal exposure during pregnancy (at approximately 31 weeks of gestation) with the suspect product Flucelvax QIV. As I was driving home after receiving Flu vaccination at Pharmacy I began having trouble breathing but thought that it must be my imagination because I was reassured by the Pharmacist that the flu vaccination was safe.  I went to bed that evening and woke up around 8:00 A.m.  drenced in sweat, achey. feeling  sick.  As I stood up from bed I passed out  hitting my side and head on the ground.  When I awoke a few minutes later I stood up again and fell into the wall hitting my head a second time and then passing out again.  When I came to a few minutes later I tried to get off the floor again only to pass out again, falling back on the floor.  I don't remember each time I hit the floor as I fainted before that.  When I came to again,  minutes later I was finally able to get up.  I spent the day on the couch, achy, vomiting, sweating with the chills.  It is several weeks since I received the vaccination and I am still achy,  coughing non stop and vomiting if I eat anything to heavy.  I can definitely see how these vaccinations could end the life of a child,  unborn fetus, elderly person or someone who wasn't as healthy as I was before the vaccination.  I  cannot begin to describe the level of regret that I have about being foolish enough to have gotten this vaccination as I was the epitome of great health before the vaccination and now pray that my body will clear itself of this poison so I can be healthy the way I was before the flu vaccination.  I am reporting this in the hopes of preventing  someone else from suffering as I have.

Drug dose administration interval too short; Intense burning sensation in all extremities (both hands and feet); Tingling; Described the pain as 'internal burning and felt like muscles were on fire'; This case was reported by a pharmacist via sales rep and described the occurrence of burning sensation in a 53-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number KJ9N5, expiry date 17th October 2021) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis, Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season) for prophylaxis and cyanocobalamin (Vitamin B12 Injection) solution for injection for an unknown indication.   The patient's past medical history included pain, numbness and mixed sensory & motor neuropathy (in both feet). Previously administered products included Gabapentin (couldn't tolerate it) and Norco. Concurrent medical conditions included diabetes.   On 11th September 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 13th October 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 11th September 2019, the patient received Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season. On an unknown date, the patient started Vitamin B12 Injection at an unknown dose and frequency. On an unknown date, less than 3 months after receiving Shingrix, Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season and Vitamin B12 Injection and not applicable after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced burning sensation, tingling, pain and drug dose administration interval too short. The patient was treated with hydrocodone bitartrate + paracetamol (Norco). On an unknown date, the outcome of the burning sensation, tingling and pain were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the drug dose administration interval too short was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the burning sensation, tingling and pain to be related to Shingrix, Fluarix Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season and Vitamin B12 Injection.  Additional details were provided as follows: The health care professional asked whether there had been any report of patient getting a mild version of shingles after receiving Shingrix. The patient received Fluarix in the left deltoid and Vitamin B 12 injection in the right deltoid. The patient reported tingling, intense internal burning sensation in all extremities(both hands and feet) and felt like her muscle were on fire. The patient thought that was due to the Shingrix and rated the pain as a 9/10 which lasted for 1 and a half day. On 3rd October 2019, the patient thought she should get 2nd dose of Shingrix. The patient had Norco at home and took some. The patient said that the pain lasted 1 and a half days and described the pain as internal burning and felt like her muscles were on fire. On 13th October 2019, the patient received 2nd dose of Shingrix which was earlier than the recommended schedule, which led to drug dose interval too short. The Health care professional assumed everything was alright. The reporter agreed to follow-up by GlaxoSmithKline.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Mixed sensory & motor neuropathy (in both feet); Numbness; Pain

D degrees Fahrenheit to 99.1 degrees Fahrenheit; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse received by Pfizer from Merck and Co., Inc. A female patient of an unspecified age received pneumococcal 13-valent conjugate vaccine (diphtheria crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13, lot/batch number and expiration date not reported), via an unspecified route of administration in the upper left arm on 25Nov2019 16:00 as single dose for immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. It was reported that about 4 p.m. on 25Nov2019, and subsequently experienced arm pain, rated at 8/10 in her left upper arm, where the vaccine was administered. Nurse reported that the patient described the pain as radiating to the shoulder blade, and down the arm to the elbow, and the pinky finger. Nurse reported that the pain began about 4 hours post vaccination. Nurse also reported that the patient's body temperature rose from a baseline of 96.5 degrees Fahrenheit to 99.1 degrees Fahrenheit, approximately 8 hours after receipt of the vaccine. Nurse reported that the following morning, the patient awoke with a severe headache, but that the arm pain, was reduced to a 6/10, but that the arm was stiff and difficult to move. Nurse reported that the patient is treating herself with 1000 mg of TYLENOL every 6 hours as well as 50 mg of BENADRYL every six hours. The outcome of the event experienced arm pain, rated at 8/10 in her left upper arm, where the vaccine was administered/ arm pain, was reduced to a 6/10 was recovering; while the rest of the events are unknown.   No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Respiratory distress; Transposition of great vessels; Foetal exposure during pregnancy; This is a observational study case, initially received on 02-Dec-2019,with additional information received on 04-Dec-2019 (being processed together), concerning a male neonate subject whose mother was a 30-year-old,  of body weight: 261 lbs, height: 65.5 inches and body mass index (BMI): 42.8, who was enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with seasonal cell culture influenza trivalent (TIVc) or quadrivalent (QIVc) vaccine during pregnancy.  The mother's current conditions included body mass index 40 and higher (reported as severely obese), stress and smoking.  The mother's concomitant medication was not provided.  The subject's mother obstetrical history noted that the she had two previous pregnancies, both with full-term live birth. The subject's mother did not have a history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). The mother's family history of major congenital malformation was collected, and the father of baby's maternal nephew had cystic fibrosis. The subject's mother did not use alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The mother was a user of tobacco. Subject's paternal age was 32.  The subject's mother last menstrual period (LMP) date was 15-Mar-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The mother's estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 20-Dec-2019 and corrected EDD was reported as 19-Nov-2019. It was reported that the subject's mother had late entry in prenatal care.   On 02-Jul-2019, the mother underwent anatomy scan and there was no MCM noted.  On 28-Aug-2019 the subject's mother received Tdap [diphtheria vaccine toxoid, pertussis vaccine acellular, tetanus vaccine toxoid, dose 0.5 mL, route of administration intramuscular] for unknown indication.  On 12-Sep-2019, at gestation age of 25 weeks, the subject's mother was administered Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD [influenza vaccine, batch number: 2612000, dose: 0.5 mL, route of administration, anatomical location, and expiry date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for unknown indication.   at gestational age of 40 weeks, the subject's mother vaginally delivered live birth, male neonate with birth weight: 3714 grams. The gestational age at outcome was 40 weeks, body length, head circumference and the appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) were not reported. There was MCM identified at birth as transposition of great vessels.  Other factors contributing to the MCM were unknown. Gestational age range for origin of the defect was three to eight weeks. Ethology of defect was reported as abnormal or absent migration of cardiac neural crest. There had been associations with maternal obesity, smoking and stress. Genetic associations also had been described. As reported, a temporal assessment was that exposure was after the origin of the defect. There was no data about scientific advisory committee (SAC) temporal assessment.  The subject was sent to another medical facility for heart defect. The subject was admitted to neonatal intensive care unit (NICU) due to respiratory distress.   At the time of initial report, the outcome of respiratory distress and transposition of great vessels was not reported.  The event of transposition of great vessels was considered as serious due to criterion of congenital anomaly and medical significance and respiratory distress was considered as serious due to medical significance.  The investigator assessed the transposition of great vessels as not related to Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD, while causality of respiratory distress was not reported. Type II mixed cryoglobulinemia; This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of the published article, titled as stated below concerning a 76 year old male patient. The patient's pertinent medical history included a bypass surgery. His concurrent conditions included coronary artery disease, hypercholesterolemia and gastroesophageal reflux disease. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.   On an unspecified date, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(manufacturer unknown) and with influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) both for prophylaxis (strength, dose, dose number, route of administration, lot number and expiration date were not reported).   On an unspecified date, five days after vaccination, the patient presented with flu-like symptoms and cyanosis of the toes and fingers. He also had nonpalpable, purpuric lesions on his toes and fingers along with acral pain. It was also reported that he progressively had worsening purpura and digital ischemia along with livedo reticularis of both plantar surfaces. Within four weeks, the patient presented anorexia, night sweats, myalgias, fatigue and arthralgias. A biopsy was offered but the patient refused to do it.   On an unspecified date, the patient had laboratory evaluation with normal findings of complete blood count, urinalysis, comprehensive metabolic panel, he also had antinuclear antibodies, antineutrophil cytoplasmatic antibodies, anticardiolipin antibodies, immunofixation eletrophoresis, hepatitis A antibody, hepatitis B surface antigen and hepatitis C antibody tests and all of them with negative results. The patient had additional tests that included rheumatoid factor at 24 IU/mL, total hemolytic complement level (CH50) at 28 (units not provided), C3 level at 75.50 mg/dL, C4 level at 1.67 mg/dL, Westergren erythrocycte sedimentation rate at 48 mm/h, high sensitive C-reactive protein at 5.24 mg/dL, antiphosphatidylserine IgG at 19 (units not provided) and antiphosphatidylserine IgM at 64 (units not provided). The patient had also a chest radiograph and doppler studies of blood flow of the extremities that were also normal. Additionally, the patient had an initial cryoglobulins test that was negative. Two weeks later, the patient had his rheumatoid factor measured and it was 54 IU/mL.  The patient then started treatment with oral prednisone 20mg daily; two weeks later, the dose was increased to 40mg daily. However, the patient continued developing acral purpuric lesions and had increasing acral pain, therefore, the patient was started on therapy with rituximab at a dose of 375 mg/mm2 weekly, four infusions total. By the fourth infusion, the patient's cryoglobulins were detected for the first time. As the patient's did not change, an additional two infusions regimen was added given monthly. Three months after the patient's last infusion with rituximab, his acral lesions healed roughly and the therapy with prednisone was slowly tapered and stopped.   Eighteen months after the patient's initial presentation, the patient had increasing acral ischemic symptoms and elevated IgM and low C4, which led to plan other four rituximab infusions. Nevertheless, after the second set of infusions, the patient developed palpable purpura on his legs. The patient then had a biopsy and leukocytoclastic vasculitis was found and direct immunofluoresencse microscopy found IgG in the vessel walls. Therefore, the patient was again treated with prednisone 40mg daily which was tapered and stopped over three weeks and the hematologist administered another another four weekly infusions of intravenous rituximab. Subsequently the patient was referred to a different facility and type II cryoglobulin was identified and characterized as IgM k monoclonal cryoglobulinemia with polyclonal IgG cryoglobulinemia. The patient also had a bone marrow biopsy and the results was normal.   Twenty months after the initial presentation, the patient started therapy with oral cyclophosphamide 100mg daily and oral prednisone 10mg daily. The patient's symptoms and clinical findings were controlled with this regimen and three years after his initial presentation, the patient's doses had been decreasing: cyclophosphamide 50mg every other day and prednisone 5mg daily, however, the patients low level of C4 persisted.   The authors stated that the mechanisms of vasculitis and cryoglobulinemia induced by pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(manufacturer unknown) or with influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) remained unknown. It was not possible to ascertain which vaccine was responsible for this patient's disease.

General information: 23 year old female, 138 pounds, 5 feet 5 inches, very active (work out 5 times a week) with no chronic illnesses, on zero medications, and with zero known allergies. No illness or sickness/cold within the past 4-5 months. Diagnosis from medical office: transverse myelitis (TM) after being hospitalized for five days at Hospital.     Symptoms Timeline:  November 26 to 28: Worst headache of my life (I never get headaches). I had throbbing neck and spinal pain. Front and back parts of the head in severe pain. Lasted over the course of 3 days. Although the headache subsided with around-the-clock Tylenol (500mg every 6-8 hours), I still had major throbbing neck/spinal pain from Nov 26 onward. I started feeling some urinary discomfort as well. The urinary discomfort was not as severe as a UTI-type feeling, but some discomfort before urinating that persisted on.   November 28th and on: Tingly-ness and numbness in upper arms, lower arms, and hands (both right and left arms). Hyper-sensitivity to arms/arm hairs. It was painful to touch anything cold (for example: when washing my hands, the cold water was horribly painful. Even the room temperature soap on my hands hurt). Numbness and ?loss of circulation-type feeling? in hands that would come and go. It felt like my hands were getting numb or going to sleep.   November 30th on: Major body aches across whole-of-body and weakness in legs in particular. I started noticing that I could not run?basically, I tried working out in the morning (my typical morning routine) and could not accelerate past a walking pace (3.5 to 4 MPH). My legs would get locked up and I would lose my balance when I tried to accelerate beyond a walking pace (My normal running pace is 7.5 MPH). I could feel intense weakness in the legs and overall body aches/pains (not muscle related, but a different type of pain). General exhaustion also was felt (sleeping much earlier than usual, etc.).   December 2: Continuation of all symptoms described above, so I decided to go to urgent Care  on the evening on December 2nd to check blood work, vitals, flu. All results came back normal, however the PAC wrote in her report that I ?must follow up with a neurologist: and to ?go to the ER immediately if any new or worsening symptoms develop. Red flags to go to ER.? Verbally she told me to get an MRI and gave me neurologist referral information.   December 3 morning: Was slated to workout in the morning, but could not physically imagine doing so due to the body aches/pain I felt while in bed. I canceled my workout class from bed. An hour later, I tried to get up to use the restroom. I could not keep my balance or walk on my feet properly. I was walking on the sides of my feet because my feet would not let me step flat. After a couple of steps, I started feeling dizzy, losing my vision, and had trouble breathing. I was aware that I was in the process of passing out, so I got on the ground and sat on the floor?gasping for air. I had my phone on me and immediately called my mother who stayed on the line (I was about to call 911 but stayed on the line with my mom). After a few seconds, I crawled to my kitchen and ate some caramelized popcorn and drank some water. I was conscious. My neighbor then came to my unit immediately and took me to the ER. I arrived at the ER around 9am.   December 3 ER: Vitals looked good. Initial testing looked normal. No flu. Their initial tests that looked at inflammation markers came back with normal results. We insisted on some neuro-related check-ups, as recommended from the urgent care PAC. ER sent me to MRI around 3PM. Results came back with many abnormalities/legions in the spinal cord in the particular. Major inflammation of the upper spinal cord and neck. Neurologist consult came in immediately and wanted to start 1000 mg steroid via IV in the ER immediately. Lumber puncture was done in the ER immediately. I was admitted to the hospital that night. From what I can see my patient chart portal, 30+ tests were done from both blood work and lumbar puncture. According to my doctors? analyses, all results have since come back normal or negative. Looks like this was not something triggered by chronic or bacterial cause.    December 3 ? 7: received 1000 mg steroid via IV per day. After day 3, most clinical symptoms such as body aches and arm tinglyness/numbness started subsiding. The treatment seemed to be working quite well. I was discharged on Saturday, December 7th. Upon discharge, I was prescribed to take a tapering steroid treatment orally (60mg for 3 days, 50 mg for 3 days, 40mg for 3 days, 30 mg for 3 days, 20 mg for 3 days, 10 mg for 3 days).   December 11: I had a follow up appointment at main Neurology with Dr. I am slated to get an MRI again on January 29th with a follow up appointment on January 29th with Dr. Additional follow ups to continue in spring and summer.

eye and vision damage; vision damage; scarring; shingles outbreaks/numbness in her left leg/Pain and tingling sensations in her skin,; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation concerning a female patient (pt) of unknown age. On 11-SEP-2017, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster).         At the beginning of January 2018, the pt experienced many shingles outbreaks causing to the pt tremendous pain, scarring (scar) and also eye (eye injury) and vision damage (visual impairment). These injuries were caused by zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). Then, the pt continued having reoccurring shingles outbreaks including extreme pain and numbness in her left leg which all resulted in medical treatment. At the reporting time, the pt was not recovered from the adverse experiences. The events were considered to be disabling.

Based on available information the role of vaccine cannot be assessed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I felt fine for the rest of the day after the shot.  That night, went to bed and woke about 2:30 AM with extreme body ache, shaking chills, upset stomach, and dizziness.  The body ache and chills were severe!  EVERYTHING seemed to ache, but particularly my hips. At 8 AM I contacted my doctor to advise her that I thought I was experiencing adverse symptoms to a Shingrix shot received the day before.  She advised me to take 1000 mg Tylenol  in 3 separate doses.  Also suggested that if a cough started I should come in promptly, as I might have simultaneously contracted a virus and could receive treatment for flu.  I followed  her advice.  No cough appeared.  Just lethargy, aches, chills.   The strong adverse symptoms continued for the entire day.  No amount of layered clothing or electrical warmers could ease the chills.  I spent a good share of the day in bed, a new experience for me!   It was a LONG DAY and  I went to sleep early evening.  Slept well.  Next morning, I woke feeling like I have felt most of my life: well, strong, energetic.  Apetite not so good, but chills, aches, dizziness, stomach upset were gone.  A 24 hour NASTY experience!
OTHER_MEDS: Calcium 600 mg (withVit D3 800 IU) Vitamin D3 25 mcg 1000IU HealthMarket Sentry Senior Women 50+ Vitamin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Extreme pain and soreness in left arm following Tdap vaccination for at least a week, pain causing sleep disturbances and inability to use arm. After about a week the extreme pain subsided to a moderate pain that only became severe when using the arm, lifting the arm, etc. Still experiencing pain, discomfort, and reduced range of motion over a month after recieving the vaccination. I can't lift left arm more than 45 degrees to the side or across the body without significant pain. Treatments so far: I took  OTC antiinflammatories for several days (that didn't really help). After three weeks of pain  I eventually visited an orthoped who prescribed a topical antiinflammatory and physical therapy, to be followed up by an MRI if the physical therapy does not resolve the issues.  I have had one session of PT so far.
LAB_DATA: None yet since the orthoped said insurance wouldn't cover an MRI unless I tried physical therapy first.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mother called same day and reports the child went home and slept for several hours and reported feeling weak and like her legs were heavy. Mother assumed it was normal side effects. The next morning she passed out while getting ready for school, had a terrible sore throat and again complained of legs feeling heavy, light headed and very tired. Mother monitored her, gave her juice and peanut butter and stayed home from school with her. She was tired and slept all day, continuing to complain of sore throat, achey and spacey says mother. This provider was called Tuesday night(12/10/19) and the father reports the child was not acting normal and was glassey eyed, staring off into space and passed out again. They were instructed to take her to the ER. Mother reports the ER physican performed lab work , Strept and Flu test and were told everything was normal and it could be a virus and or possible reaction to flu vaccine.  Wednesday morning,  mother reports  she slept for hours and reported feeling exhausted, no fever during the entire time. Thursday, mother reports she was still weak and just wanted to sleep and lay around. Today she returned to the office for follow up from the ER visit. Patient and mother reports she is feeling some better, no sore throat, no fever, no cough, earache, vomiting or diarrhea. The patients reports continued feelings of being tired and just wants to lay around but not as bad as the first few days after the immunization.
LAB_DATA: 12/9/19 she was tested for Strept and a throat culture sent which was normal. She was seen in an outside ER-Hospital (12/10/19) and had Strept, Flu testing and lab work which were all reported as normal to the parents.
CUR_ILL: Sore throat-no fever. Rapid Strept, Flu, Throat culture normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a shot while in good health Wed afternoon at 4pm.  I had a sore arm that night.  I awakened to void at 6 am Thursday morning.--and felt perfectly normal in and out and in again,  of bed.   There was the sudden onset about 655 AM  (while still in bed) of rapidly progressive right leg numbness and weakness.  It started in upper buttock/thigh and quickly went all the way down to the toes within mere minutes.  There wasn't much for pain, just a leg that instantly stopped working. I tried to get out of bed, and fell,  later fainted in the kitchen.  I was transported to the ER, where stroke protocol ruled out stroke.  Guillen Barre was felt unlikely.   Labs, brain MR were fine.  After a back MRI, the ER doctor suggested a tiny S1 disc herniation contacting the left S1 nerve was the cause of this complete loss of leg function across the L4-S1 nerve roots.?.   While I can accept this is possible, pain really hasn't been an issue. I can put on my right sock, no problem which hasn't been the case with past sciatica spells   I just want to document this event as it seems so weird, and I am seeing a neurologist as the sciatica diagnosis seems "shaky."    I am a physician and fully accept this may not relate to the flu shot, but the timing and course is so bizarre. As of today(Friday), I am now using a cane to assist walking.
LAB_DATA: Lab, EKG, Brain MRI, lumbar mri
HISTORY: Chronic sacro-illiac pain with HLAB27 positivity

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 13:18:04 checked into pharmacy For Flu shot. Sat on bench waiting For Wife to pick up a Few groceries. About 14:00 P.M. Grandson stopped to talk to me, he noticed L side of face drooping. I checked out groceries at 14:30:03 pm. Went to restaurant to eat. Sat across from my husband Noticed L side of Face drooping. Checked for signs of stroke None Noted, walking, talking ok, NO ARM weakness, no slurred speech, Eating & drinking OK. Arrived home checked again for stroke symptoms, NONe, gave him a 325 mg. aspirin, watched him closely aLL day. Night. In morning Looked worse, could not drink without straw. Took him to Hospital ER. While checking in they said a nurse had a Flu shot & got Bell's palsy. Seen Dr. and another Dr., stated Bell's Palsy, very rare but happens. Ordered Lab drawn & brain scan. Put him on Valacyclovir HCL 1 gram t. 21 tabs -1- tab every 8hrs for -7- days & Prednisone 20 mg tabs -3- tabs a day For -7- days & eye drops, said ENT Dr. usually takes care of this. We had an appointment with Dr. Nov 7th said okay to wait untill then. Dr. said Full blown Bell's Palsy, added Prednisone packet For -6- more days. Could not close L eye, continue with eye drops, showed me how to tape eye shut at Not time. Noticed eye getting red & yellowish green drainage so took him to Ophthalmologist Dr, changed meds and showed me how to tape eye the right way, stated, can get ulcer in cornia. Eye has to be checked every 4-6 wks. Patient has difficulty seein eating, has to drink with a straw. I took him to his Family Dr., have seen Dr. three times, Dr 2 times, have appointment 01-14-2020 Have heard of three others plus patient got Bells Palsy after getting the Flu shot. My husband is depressed over it.

acoustic neuroma; right facial numbness; Shingles; Patient was diagnosed with trigeminal neuropathy; hearing loss; This initial spontaneous report was received on 06-DEC-2019, from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. The patient's pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications were not reported. On or around 21-SEP-2016, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (the dosage regimen information was not reported). Shortly after vaccination, the patient suffered right sided facial numbness and blisters, the patient was diagnosed with trigeminal neuropathy and herpes zoster/shingles. Shortly after this episode, she started to experience facial numbness and hearing deficit of the right ear. The patient was hospitalized and diagnosed with acoustic neuroma, right facial numbness, and hearing loss of the right ear. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination, the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to vaccination. She also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition, severe, serious, incurable, progressive and permanent personal injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of patient's vaccination, she had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. At the time of the report, the patient's outcome was not recovered. The adverse events were considered as medically significant by the reporter as they were serious.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came to pharmacy to receive annual flu shot. Screening form and billing processing were completed as usual. When needle was inserted into patient's arm no reaction, however when the plunger was depressed to administer the vaccine the patient had an involuntary "jolt" and pulled away and to her right. The movement pulled the arm away from the needle and the dose was incompletely administered. Some of the liquid did remain on the patient's upper arm, but some also squirted onto the floor. Some residual dose left in the prefilled syringe as well. The area was re-swabbed with an alcohol wipe to remove the vaccine liquid from the skin and the patient waited in the counseling room while I (the administering pharmacist) called the manufacturer to ask what the appropriate protocol was. They advised that any administration of their flu vaccine that resulted in less than the entire 0.5 mL quantity being injected into the muscle would be considered to provide inadequate immunity to the flu virus strains. The protocol was, therefore, to administer a dose as if the first incident had not occurred. Another pre-filled syringe from the same box as the first was taken out and administered to the patient using normal administration protocol and did not result in any further incident.

On Sept. 5, 2019, I went to the Pharmacy to pick up a prescription. I was approached by a young woman in a white coat who suggested that I should get a shingles vaccine.  I asked about side effects and asked for literature.  I was not provided any information (no brochure): the woman stated that the vaccine was safe ? she sold me on the ?Shingrix? vaccine.   Since the woman was wearing a white coat, I thought she must be a new pharmacist.  However, I had not seen her before, nor have I seen her since:  I suspect that she was a drug company salesperson.  I have since reviewed the material regarding ?Shingrix?.  Had I been aware of the potential for harm I would not have agreed to the vaccination.  Further, I am informed by my personal physician that because of my health history, I should never have received the vaccination.  On awakening the morning of Sept. 6, 2019, I had sharp pain in my lower legs: a burning sensation (hot and prickly).   Thereafter I have developed weakness in my legs such that I cannot walk without pain.  I must use a cane or crutches.  Thereafter I made an appointment with a Neurologist; tests showed severe peripheral neuropathy.   Shortly thereafter I consulted with my acupuncturist who is very familiar with my health history over the past 25 years.  In her opinion, the condition is most likely a vaccine reaction.  This diagnosis was confirmed by my primary care physician.  At present my treatment plan includes: (1) weekly acupuncture treatments; (2) weekly physical therapy; (3) weekly massage therapy; and (4) 3 times weekly chiropractic laser treatment.    I am advised that the nerve damage is permanent and potential for a cure is slim: I can barely walk.  Summary:  Based on the facts and the opinions of my several health care providers, I am convinced that I have been injured by improper administration of Shingrix vaccine.  Prior to the injury and since the time of my youth I have been very physically active (intercollegiate competitive athlete).  At the time of the injury I was active in a family owned business in which I can no longer function.  My husband and I are being forced to close the business.   My ability to maintain my home is severely impaired and the costs of my treatment and assistance with home maintenance are a significant burden.  At present I am in the process of re-activating my professional licensing: I am a qualified Mental Health Counselor.  I am scheduled to take the licensing examination in January.  My opportunities are limited by the crippling condition.
LAB_DATA: My neurologist is Dr who performed a nerve response test on my legs and has the report.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 10/13/2019 - 12 days after flu shot, he developed numbness of face, feet, and then hands,  and "abnormal hot and cold sensations."  Taken to ER, had negative stroke work up (Head CT, MRA) and stroke ruled out so he left and went home. Next morning awoke and was having diplopia,  was paralyzed in both  his feet, was unable to walk, both hands became more numb, unable to grasp objects, areflexia, returned to ER, was diagnosed with Guillain Barr�. Became confused, speech garbled, developed left facial paralysis and eyelid droop, and right sided facial weakness, was lethargic for couple days. LP showed increased number of lymphocytes, elevated protein; Was transferred to higher level of care on 10/18/2019 to Medical Center. Truncal ataxia was noted at that time, reflexes absent, unable to sit up,  still unable to walk. Had further work up,  lots of lab tests, repeat LP similar; CXR showed some old calcified nodes, so underwent bronchoscopy looking for  possible sarcoid but no granulomas were seen in specimens.  Was treated with 5 days of IVIG with signs of slight improvement over that period of time, continued to very slowly improve, , diplopia and Facial CN findings resolved, continued with numbness and weakness of all 4 extremities with very slow improvement.  Given IV steroids after the IVIG, and then switched to oral prednisone. Was hospitalized until November 6, 2019, then transferred to Skilled Nursing Facility, to receive physical therapy, continued on  prednisone.  Final diagnosis was Acute inflammatory polyneuropathy.   Still in Skilled Nursing Facility, very slow recovery of function, still unable to walk independently, somewhat slurred speech, some word finding difficulty. My impression (Not the attending )   Diagnosis is consistent with Bickenstaff's  Brainstem encephalitis with Guillain Barr� following Flu shot..

CSF on 1021/19: Tube 1: 467 RBCs,  8 WBC,(lymphocytes predominance)  protein >600. Tube 4: 101 RBCs 16 WBCs lymphocyte "predominance." I received the MMR as a child.  I wanted to get a booster to be on the safe side due to the localized outbreak.  Approx one week after receiving the booster vaccination, At 4am, I awoke with the left Submandibular Gland swollen.  No fever, no pain, felt fine other than a slight hangover from drinking 3 bourbon and cokes the night before.  Other than that, I felt fine.  The following day, the left Submandibular gland was still swollen, so I went to Hospital?s urgent care.  They tested for Mumps, and quarantined me for five days.  By Saturday the noticeable swelling was gone, and I felt slightly under the weather, but more annoyed that I was quarantined and missing out on the weekend.  By Sunday, I was feeling completely fine.  The only medicine taken during this time was My daily Triumeq.  I do not take any OTC medicine, unless it is direly needed.  Monday, I awoke with the left Parotid gland swollen about the size of a silver dollar.  It was noticeable and slightly discomfortable, but not painful.  On Tuesday the sweeping was still there, so I took 600mg on time of ibuprofen.  It didn?t seem to do anything for the swelling, so I didn?t take it again.  The swelling very gradually subsided, and by Friday it was not noticeable without me pointing it out.  By this past Saturday, there was slight swelling, but only noticeable to two doctors  that I just happened to meet out and about, and I was telling them about the experience.  After looking at my face, intrigued, they noticed the very slight swelling still, and told me that I should file this report and monitor myself for the next couple of weeks.

strained muscle of rotator cuff; Shoulder pain; restricted range of motion following injection of IIV into the upper arm; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of rotator cuff injury in a elderly patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine. On an unknown date, less than a week after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced rotator cuff injury (serious criteria hospitalization and other: as per reporter), injected limb mobility decreased (serious criteria hospitalization and other: as per reporter) and shoulder pain (serious criteria hospitalization and other: as per reporter). On an unknown date, the outcome of the rotator cuff injury, injected limb mobility decreased and shoulder pain were unknown.   The reporter considered the rotator cuff injury, injected limb mobility decreased and shoulder pain to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of shoulder pain with strained muscle of rotator cuff patient aged between 24 and 92 years of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with unspecified inactivated seasonal influenza vaccine (IIV) (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. The patient was a part of descriptive analysis that aimed to describe case reports of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following injection of inactivated influenza vaccine (IIV). The data searched from the vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) database from July 2010 to June 2017 for reports of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following IIV. [In this study, the classified reports into three categories: confirmed (i.e., met the criteria of our case definition), indeterminate, or not a case. Reports that met the regulatory definition for serious were independently reviewed by the physician. Excluded reports that described symptoms lasting less than 7 days and those in which the report date was less than 7 days following vaccination]. The patient had no brachial neuritis. The patient had not received more than one vaccine was administered in the arm of the affected shoulder (multiple vaccinations not given simultaneously) and the patient had no prior history of chronic pain, inflammation, or injury with recurrent symptoms in the affected shoulder. The patient was from confirmed serious case category. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received unspecified inactivated influenza vaccine (IIV) in the upper arm (administration route unspecified; dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date between 1st July 2010 and 30th June 2017 (2010-2011 through 2016-2017 influenza seasons), less than 48 hours after vaccination, the patient had experienced shoulder pain with strained muscle of rotator cuff and was hospitalized. [In this study, case definition or criteria included shoulder pain and restricted range of motion following injection of IIV into the upper arm with symptom onset less than 48 h after IIV vaccination and a duration of greater than seven days (to differentiate from injection site reactions). The patient discharged. This case has been considered serious due to hospitalization and as per author. [In this study, for the purpose of IIV vaccination among the 90 cases that met the regulatory definition of serious as specified in Regulations defined as a report was classified as serious if any of the following were described death, life-threatening illness, hospitalization or prolongation of existing hospitalization, permanent disability, congenital anomaly or birth defect, or intervention to prevent the aforementioned outcomes].  Treatment was unknown. [In this study, eight of the 11 hospitalized cases described patients who underwent surgery of the affected shoulder joint. Treatments prescribed in 546 reports, of those 254 non-narcotic analgesics; 215 physical therapy; 109 corticosteroid injection; 89 hot and cold therapy; 79 oral steroids; 28 narcotic analgesics; 19 home shoulder exercise; 17 pain medication; not specified; 16 surgery; 15 muscle relaxants;10 topical analgesics; 10 massage; 7 chiropractic; 6 sling; 4 acupuncture; 2 shoulder manipulation under sedation; 2 antibiotics; 2 muscle stimulators; other includes: rest, restrictions for arm, shoulder taped, anticonvulsants, iontophoresis, sedatives, fluids, yoga, mud patches, and treatment not specified]. The outcome of the events were not reported. [In the study, in 1057 reports, signs and symptoms had not resolved at the time a report was made to VAERS]. In 50 reports, symptoms had resolved at time of report; median duration to recovery was 70 days (range 18-365 days). The remaining 113 reports did not state whether the symptoms had resolved.]. The authors commented, "This was the first large-scale, post-licensure vaccine safety review of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following influenza vaccination. Our results suggest that reports of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following IIV were uncommon, given the amount of influenza vaccine distributed." we cannot conclude that these reports represent true incident shoulder injuries caused by vaccination. However, we also cannot rule out that some of these cases might be new shoulder injuries or aggravation of existing shoulder injuries resulting from improperly administered vaccines too close to the underlying structures and tissues of the shoulder joint. Reasons for the increase in shoulder injury related to vaccine administration (SIRVA) claims filed with the Compensation Program (CP) were likely due to factors other than a true increase in causally-associated vaccine-related shoulder injuries. The CP covers all vaccines routinely recommended for use in children regardless of the age of the vaccine recipient. While we cannot establish cause and effect based on VAERS reports, these findings suggest that improper placement of an intramuscular vaccine injection too high on the arm and too close to the underlying structures of the shoulder joint might be a possible contributing factor for atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction. It is possible that some individuals in our analysis had minor shoulder problems unrelated to vaccination that would subsequently resolve; however, in most reports, we were unable to determine how long the shoulder pain and dysfunction persisted because reports were made to VAERS while patients were still experiencing signs and symptoms. Reported contributing factors, such as IIV given ��too high" on the arm are primarily subjective, self-reported, and not verifiable. In most reports, documentation of past medical history was limited so pre-existing shoulder problems or other risk factors that could explain signs and symptoms might not have been identified. However, based on VAERS reports alone, we cannot draw any conclusions about a potential association with respect to place of vaccination. The author concluded, "Reports to VAERS of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following IIV were relatively uncommon and stable during the seven influenza seasons in our review, with no indication of a recent increase in reporting. In total, we identified 1220 reports during a time period in which almost 1 billion doses of IIV had been distributed. Some of these case reports might represent true shoulder injuries that were caused or aggravated by an improperly administered vaccine. If some of these reports are the result of poor injection technique then they are preventable. Healthcare provider awareness, education and training, and adherence to best practices for vaccine administration are important focus areas for prevention. CDC has resources available on safe vaccine administration practices. Efforts to address healthcare practice issues around potential shoulder injuries related to vaccination could include the development of a standardized case definition similar to what has been done with local injection site reactions, evaluation of pathophysiology and risk factors, and determining best injection practices and effective prevention and treatment options." This is 1 of the 6 valid cases reported in this literature article.

However, we also cannot rule out that some of these cases might be new shoulder injuries or aggravation of existing shoulder injuries resulting from improperly administered vaccines too close to the underlying structures and tissues of the shoulder joint. Reasons for the increase in shoulder injury related to vaccine administration (SIRVA) claims filed with the Compensation Program (CP) were likely due to factors other than a true increase in causally-associated vaccine-related shoulder injuries. The CP covers all vaccines routinely recommended for use in children regardless of the age of the vaccine recipient. While we cannot establish cause and effect based on VAERS reports, these findings suggest that improper placement of an intramuscular vaccine injection too high on the arm and too close to the underlying structures of the shoulder joint might be a possible contributing factor for atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction. It is possible that some individuals in our analysis had minor shoulder problems unrelated to vaccination that would subsequently resolve; however, in most reports, we were unable to determine how long the shoulder pain and dysfunction persisted because reports were made to VAERS while patients were still experiencing signs and symptoms. Reported contributing factors, such as IIV given ��too high" on the arm are primarily subjective, self-reported, and not verifiable. In most reports, documentation of past medical history was limited so pre-existing shoulder problems or other risk factors that could explain signs and symptoms might not have been identified. However, based on VAERS reports alone, we cannot draw any conclusions about a potential association with respect to place of vaccination. The author concluded, "Reports to VAERS of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following IIV were relatively uncommon and stable during the seven influenza seasons in our review, with no indication of a recent increase in reporting. In total, we identified 1220 reports during a time period in which almost 1 billion doses of IIV had been distributed. Some of these case reports might represent true shoulder injuries that were caused or aggravated by an improperly administered vaccine. If some of these reports are the result of poor injection technique then they are preventable. Healthcare provider awareness, education and training, and adherence to best practices for vaccine administration are important focus areas for prevention. CDC has resources available on safe vaccine administration practices. Efforts to address healthcare practice issues around potential shoulder injuries related to vaccination could include the development of a standardized case definition similar to what has been done with local injection site reactions, evaluation of pathophysiology and risk factors, and determining best injection practices and effective prevention and treatment options." This is 1 of the 6 valid cases reported in this literature article.
