[In this study, for the purpose of IIV vaccination among the 90 cases that met the regulatory definition of serious as specified in Regulations defined as a report was classified as serious if any of the following were described death, life-threatening illness, hospitalization or prolongation of existing hospitalization, permanent disability, congenital anomaly or birth defect, or intervention to prevent the aforementioned outcomes].  Treatment was unknown. [In this study, eight of the 11 hospitalized cases described patients who underwent surgery of the affected shoulder joint. Treatments prescribed in 546 reports, of those 254 non-narcotic analgesics; 215 physical therapy; 109 corticosteroid injection; 89 hot and cold therapy; 79 oral steroids; 28 narcotic analgesics; 19 home shoulder exercise; 17 pain medication; not specified; 16 surgery; 15 muscle relaxants;10 topical analgesics; 10 massage; 7 chiropractic; 6 sling; 4 acupuncture; 2 shoulder manipulation under sedation; 2 antibiotics; 2 muscle stimulators; other includes: rest, restrictions for arm, shoulder taped, anticonvulsants, iontophoresis, sedatives, fluids, yoga, mud patches, and treatment not specified]. The outcome of the events were not reported. [In the study, in 1057 reports, signs and symptoms had not resolved at the time a report was made to VAERS]. In 50 reports, symptoms had resolved at time of report; median duration to recovery was 70 days (range 18-365 days). The remaining 113 reports did not state whether the symptoms had resolved.]. The authors commented, "This was the first large-scale, post-licensure vaccine safety review of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following influenza vaccination. Our results suggest that reports of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following IIV were uncommon, given the amount of influenza vaccine distributed." we cannot conclude that these reports represent true incident shoulder injuries caused by vaccination. However, we also cannot rule out that some of these cases might be new shoulder injuries or aggravation of existing shoulder injuries resulting from improperly administered vaccines too close to the underlying structures and tissues of the shoulder joint. Reasons for the increase in shoulder injury related to vaccine administration (SIRVA) claims filed with the Compensation Program (CP) were likely due to factors other than a true increase in causally-associated vaccine-related shoulder injuries. The CP covers all vaccines routinely recommended for use in children regardless of the age of the vaccine recipient. While we cannot establish cause and effect based on VAERS reports, these findings suggest that improper placement of an intramuscular vaccine injection too high on the arm and too close to the underlying structures of the shoulder joint might be a possible contributing factor for atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction. It is possible that some individuals in our analysis had minor shoulder problems unrelated to vaccination that would subsequently resolve; however, in most reports, we were unable to determine how long the shoulder pain and dysfunction persisted because reports were made to VAERS while patients were still experiencing signs and symptoms. Reported contributing factors, such as IIV given ��too high" on the arm are primarily subjective, self-reported, and not verifiable. In most reports, documentation of past medical history was limited so pre-existing shoulder problems or other risk factors that could explain signs and symptoms might not have been identified. However, based on VAERS reports alone, we cannot draw any conclusions about a potential association with respect to place of vaccination. The author concluded, "Reports to VAERS of atypical shoulder pain and dysfunction following IIV were relatively uncommon and stable during the seven influenza seasons in our review, with no indication of a recent increase in reporting. In total, we identified 1220 reports during a time period in which almost 1 billion doses of IIV had been distributed. Some of these case reports might represent true shoulder injuries that were caused or aggravated by an improperly administered vaccine. If some of these reports are the result of poor injection technique then they are preventable. Healthcare provider awareness, education and training, and adherence to best practices for vaccine administration are important focus areas for prevention. CDC has resources available on safe vaccine administration practices. Efforts to address healthcare practice issues around potential shoulder injuries related to vaccination could include the development of a standardized case definition similar to what has been done with local injection site reactions, evaluation of pathophysiology and risk factors, and determining best injection practices and effective prevention and treatment options." This is 1 of the 6 valid cases reported in this literature article.

On or around 04-AUG-2017, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster).  On an unknown (reported as shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX)), the patient suffered herpes zoster along the left side of abdomen, benign paroxysmal positional vertigo, bilateral tinnitus and hearing loss(deafness).  As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product.  The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition.  As a result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries.  Further, as a tragic consequence of the Company's wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury.  As a direct and proximate result of the Company's conduct, the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.  The outcome of the events were considered not recovered/not resolved.  The events were considered related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  All the events were considered to be disabling.  Upon internal review, the event deafness was considered to be medically significant.  Additional information has been requested.

1st dose in November 2016, 2nd dose 3-4 months later and 3rd dose in March 2017.; brain is in a fog; has cognitive impairment, is anxious and withdrawn; has cognitive impairment, is anxious and withdrawn/teenage angst; has cognitive impairment, is anxious and withdrawn; He mumbles when he talks/When he talks, he says he doesn't know what to say; This spontaneous report was received from a consumer referring to a 15 years old male patient. The patient had no concomitant medications, pertinent medical history and drug reactions/allergies.     In November 2016, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) (dose, lot # and expiration date were not provided) intramuscularly for prophylaxis. The second dose  was administered 3-4 months later and the third dose  was administered in March 2017 (via intramuscular; dose detail, lot number and expire date were unknown) (inappropriate schedule of product administration).        In 2017 (reported as after 2nd dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9)), the patient was noticed different and had cognitive impairment, was anxious and withdrawn. The patient felt the shot going through his veins. He mumbled when he talked. When he talked, he said he didn't know what to say since he said his brain was in a fog. His teachers at school said he was like a different person. At first the reporter thought it was teenage angst. The patient sought for medical attention. The patient went to a mental therapist who prescribed fluoxetine hydrochloride (PROZAC) and sertraline hydrochloride (ZOLOFT). That didn't help so they were discontinued. He went to a Neurologist who did lab panel for aluminum which didn't show anything. The patient tried probiotics, changing diet to fruits and vegetables, yogurt, lemongrass, elderberry, epsom salt baths, cilantro, fish oil supplements, Cannabidiol (CBD) oil and deep tissue massage. Nothing seemed to help. The outcome of the events was not recovered. The causality assessment was not provided.  Upon internal review, brain was in a fog was determined to be medically significant.

This case involves a 71 years old female patient who developed macular degeneration (macular degeneration), opened her eyes saw a flashing light, moving back and forth in the room (photopsia) and headache (headache), while she received vaccine INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE [FLUZONE HIGH DOSE].  Medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided. At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing Blindness unilateral.    On 30-Nov-2019, the patient received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE (lot number and expiry date not reported) via unknown route in right arm.  On 01-Dec-2019, the patient developed a non-serious opened her eyes saw a flashing light, moving back and forth in the room (photopsia), one days following the administration of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE.  On an unknown date, the patient experienced a serious macular degeneration (macular degeneration), unknown latency following the administration of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE. This event was assessed as medically significant.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a non-serious headache (headache), unknown latency following the administration of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE.  Other relevant tests were not reported.  Final diagnosis was macular degeneration, headache and photopsia.  The patient was treated with ASPIRIN [ACETYLSALICYLIC ACID] for Headache.  The outcome was not reported for macular degeneration.  The patient was not recovered from photopsia and was recovering from headache.  Information on the batch number was requested.; Sender's Comments: This case involves a 71 years old female patient who presented with macular degeneration, photopsia and headache after vaccination with FLUZONE HIGH DOSE. The outcome of the events of ADEM and shingles were considered as not recovered. The reporter considered ADEM and shingles to be related to Zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 5 hours after my son, 6 weeks old at the time, had his wellness visit and all his vaccines, he started to sleep very heavily, he was unresponsive, he woke to projectile vomit and it was highly unusual, he was burning up with a fever (the fever was below the offices recommended rate at when you would bring him to the emergency room), he was having projectile diarrhea. He was obviously having severe reactions to the vaccines, I didn't know it until I asked fellow mothers who have gone through this same experience. I called the emergency line at approximately midnight, nearly 10 hours after the vaccines, at this point he was not waking up without me forcefully waking him so he wouldn't fall into a deep sleep, at times he would not wake up even to me saying his name and gently nudging him and patting his back, etc, he is an exclusively breast fed baby that has ALWAYS nursed on demand, he has ALWAYS woke every 2 hours to nurse, this is how I knew immediately that something was very, very wrong during the first 5 to 10 hrs, when I got through to the emergency doctor on the emergency line, she shrugged off all my concerns, she told me THIS WAS NORMAL, she said I was a "first time mom" and that I was over reacting and panicking for no reason etc, I told her this is not normal and I know my son's patterns, behavior, and his routine. She told me to give him Tylenol which is known to cause more extreme and adverse side effects after vaccines. I told her it didn't seem right, she told me to do it and he would be fine, I did not give him Tylenol because his immune sytem would not be able to fight the fever or clear the new toxins present if I gave him that dose of Tylenol as she suggested. They still have that recording and I will ask them to pull that recording if need be, to prove that this doctor dismissed these huge issues, she downplayed his adverse reactions to the vaccines, she mocked me, then proceeded to tell me she's "been doing this for 40+ years" that she knows what she's talking about, etc.. I did not bring my son to the E.R., I nursed him and I stayed away the entire week, I did not sleep, because I knew if I slept that my son would not wake back up ever again, he was very close to death after these vaccines, it took a full week for him to slowly come back to normal, he would not look us in the eyes like he did prior to the vaccines, he was groggy and zombie like, he was sluggish and unresponsive, he would do blood curdling screams towards the end of the week, as if he was in pain, my poor son went through more than any child should endure at the young age of 6 weeks, it's sad our family went through this and my son endured this after we knew that this seemed wrong.
OTHER_MEDS: Baby D drops, 1 drop per day per exclusively breast fed.
CUR_ILL: He was still sick with a cold, he was only 6 weeks old and 6 pounds due to IUGR, we expressed these concerns with both the nurse and the doctor present for this appointment and they both said he would be fine and it wasn't an issue to worry about.

She was told at that time it was a frozen shoulder and referred her to an orthopedic.   The orthopedic determined the problem was SIRVA and put her on an oral steroid for 6 days.  She returned to the orthopedic for a follow up on December 16, the oral steroid had not helped the issue, so she was given a steroid injection and was then referred for physical therapy. By 2.5 years, he developed hypotonia, recurrent respiratory infections, and chronic diarrhea. On unknown dates (reported as "concurrently"), his labs demonstrated absolute T-cell lymphopenia (708 cells/micro-L), immunoglobulin G (IgG) deficiency (235 mg/dl) and undetectable titers to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(manufacturer unknown) and measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live(manufacturer unknown). Patient was fine and chatting for the first 2 to 3 minutes after vaccine. I had her sit down in the waiting area - very close to my workstation. I counseled her to let me know if she was feeling dizzy or any different than baseline. I made eye contact and she gave me a thumbs up after about 5 minutes from administration of vaccine. At about the 7 minute mark, I noticed she placed her hand on her forehead, so I went closer to ask if she was alright. I said her name, she looked up at me,  then asked if she was feeling ok. She just had a plain, squinting look as if she was extremely confused and couldn't understand what I was saying. I immediately went out and sat next to her. She hunched over in her chair and was extremely confused. I immediately had my intern call 9-1-1. I asked her what her name was, and had to repeat the question three times before she answered. Asked her to smile for me - no noted facial droop, but again had to ask her twice before she understood. EMT came and brought her to the hospital, and she was admitted (they called that evening to verify her meds as she was being admitted.) I called the patient to follow up with her this morning, 12/18/19, and she said that she was in the hospital from 12/14/19, to 12/15/19, and was discharged home with PT and OT therapy assigned to her. She said that, "they think she may have had a stroke", but couldn't recall much of the details. She stated that she is feeling much better, but seemed a little unsure of what all had happened.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient developed fever and irritability on Saturday November 16th around 3pm. Full dose of 1.875 mL of infant's motrin given approximately 3:15pm. Patient was put to sleep around 7pm and awoke several times due to fever. Second full dose of motrin given around 9:45pm. Rectal temperature taken around 11pm upon waking. Temperature was 103.9. Patient was crying and upset throughout the night. Around 2am patient was jerking quickly and repeatedly while crying, which lasted for about 2 minutes. Jerking occured again around 5am and lasted for 2-3 minutes, about one jerk every 5-10 seconds. 3rd dose of motrin given around 5am.  Rectal temperature taken around 5am; result was 103.4. Patient was extremely upset and irritable and appeared to be in pain. Around 5:30am decided he should be seen at the ER.  Patient's fever lasted for 4 days, subsiding on Tuesday November 19th. Patient was lethargic and unable to stay awake for more than  2 hours at a time throughout the day from Sunday November 17th-Friday November 22nd. Patient was lethargic and unresponsive; he was not able to stay awake for more than 2 hours at a time and slept 5-7 hours a day and 12-13 hours at night. His behavior was dramatically different as he is usually very active and aware. Patient began returning to normal behavior on Friday November 22nd; total adverse event lasted for 6 days.
LAB_DATA: ER doctor examined patient and saw no sign of illness. No ear infection. Patient did not have a cold or any other symptoms of other infection at time of admittance. ER doctor said that fever was most likely a result of the MMR vaccine as it was 10 days post vaccination.
CUR_ILL: No illness  at time of vaccination. Patient experienced mild case of hand foot mouth disease from October 25-28.
PRIOR_VAX: patient routinely experiences fever from 102-102.5 for 2-5 days after a vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the second dose .shingrix vaccine on October 21st. Within 12 hours, i felt ill, flu- like symptoms which lasted app 24 hrs. On December 1st, I experienced R cranial nerve pain and within 36 hrs I presented to an acute care hospital ER with a dx of r/o stroke - having symptoms of numbness around mouth, slurred speech, drooping R side mouth and severe drooping R eye, I am an otherwise healthy, active senior citizen with no hx of Bell's Palsy or other related dx.
LAB_DATA: CT BRAIN 04-Dec-2019 Negative CHEM PANEL 04-Dec-2019 Negative EKG 04-Dec-2019 Negative All tests = negative. I was immediately treated with prednisone and placed on a 7day, tapered regime of prednisone and an antiviral. Standard current treatment for .bell's Palsy. I understand that there is nothing reported in the literature that might lead to a suspicion about a connection between .shingrix and Bell's Palsy, however, since origin of both is viral and there isn't much known about Shingrix, I want to add my experience in the hope that it may lead to a scientific connection and /or at least an investigation into the possibility.
OTHER_MEDS: Hydrochlorithyizide, Lipitor Calcium, fish oil, vitamin A, B 12, D. Biotin, iron, multivitamin
CUR_ILL: Non smoker, no concomitant medical disease
HISTORY: Minor hypertension- treated High cholesterol- treated

On 10/16 I received the flu shot from  a coworker. I am an RN and getting the flu shot is mandatory for all of us. When she injected the vaccine I looked over at my shoulder because it was more painful than usual and I was also surprised at how high up on my arm it was.  Within 30 minutes of receiving the injection I was experiencing abnormal sensations in my 4th and fifth fingers on my L hand and the sensation that my wrist watch was cutting off my circulation although I could (in actuality) slip a finger between the band and my skin. My shoulder had a deep ache within it and I had deep pain at the injection site. I reported this to my supervisor and was seen by, PA, the Associate Medical Director. She agreed the symptoms were concerning and asked me to update her. That night the abnormal sensations resolved but the joint pain worsened and by the morning I could barely move it above my head. I texted PA and she recommended I see my PCP. I made an appointment with my PCP for next available (Monday  10/20) but I cancelled it because it felt like I had the pain under control and didn't want to miss work. Over the next few days I took Motrin in high amounts, used hot packs and ice packs. This continued through the next week. This same week I began having a spastic cough, severe pain in my ribs and abdominals as well as difficulty catching my breath or taking a deep breath. I ended up in urgent care due to this issue on  10/25.   I stopped taking Motrin and the pain  in my shoulder came back, but even worse during the evening on 10/27. The pain woke me from my sleep . I made an appointment with my PCP and went to see Dr. for both my shoulder pain and the respiratory issue on 10/29.  Dr. put me on a burst of oral steroids from  10/30 - 11/3 for the shortness of breath/coughing. During this time, I also experienced complete respite from the shoulder pain and enjoyed my full range of motion and strength for the first time since the vaccine was given. She also sent a referral for me to see an orthopedist.   I saw Dr., (an orthopedist) on  11/15. At the time of our appointment I was not in pain because I was actually back on steroids (11/12-11/16) for continued respiratory symptoms.  He opted to not give me a cortisone injection because of the oral steroids I was receiving. He prescribed physical therapy to me and told me to come back when I was off the oral steroids if PT did not resolve the issue.  My PCP diagnosed me with SIRVA. (Shoulder Injury Related to Vaccine Administration).  I have been in PT since 11/18. I am still symptomatic except for when I am on oral steroids.  I have an MRI scheduled for 12/29 and a corticosteroid injection  scheduled for 1/2/20.

I went to my physician's office to receive the Shingrix vaccination.  I received the immunization  at approximately 2:00 pm.  By 8:00 pm the same day, I had chills and went to bed.  During the night, I woke up with a 103.6 temperature.  I took over the counter medication to reduce my fever.  The second day, I would have chills and run a temperature at around 101.  Again, I took over the counter medication.  The second night, I had a night sweat that was so fierce, my entire bed including sheets, blankets and comforter were completely soaked.  Today is day 3 and no fever, but now I feel cold and weak.  I sincerely regret taking this vaccination and will recommend to family and friends to refrain from taking it.  I don't think I had a "mild" reaction is a fever of 103.6.  If it went any higher, I would have gone to the emergency room.  I had shingles in my early 20's.  I'd take that again any day over this vaccination.  I hope I am going to feel better soon.

stage 3 sarcoma; My son received his first dose of varivax on April 29, 2013/My son also received his first dose of MMR II on April 29, 2013; super bug; Huge haemorrhage; ear and chest infection; pneumonia like symptoms; ear and chest infection; problems peeing; constipated; had infections; nut allergy; allergy to certain soaps; This spontaneous report as received from a consumer refers to her son, a patient of approximately 7 years of age. The patient's medical history included eczema and the use of Penicillin. The patient also had a head to toe reaction to unspecified vaccinations as a child the time frame of which was not known. The patient had drug reaction/allergy to Penicillin. The patient's concomitant medication included cefdinir. On 29-APR-2013, the patient was vaccinated with first doses of varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) (Strength, dose, route, lot # and expiry date were not reported) and Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R-II) (Strength, route, lot # and expiry date were not reported) in the left arm for prophylaxis as per physician's recommendations (Inappropriate schedule of product administration). On 01-FEB-2017, the patient was vaccinated with an another dose of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R-II) recombinant Human albumin (rHA) of lot #M034857, expiration date not reported, upon internal validation established as 27-JUL-2018. The Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R-II) was reconstituted with the sterile diluent of lot # N019616. On 26-SEP-2017, the patient was vaccinated with another dose of varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) of lot # N017399, expiration date not reported, but upon internal validation established as 07-JUN-2019). The varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) was reconstituted with the sterile diluent of lot # M034194. On an unknown date (also reported as "prior to the diagnosis with stage 3 sarcoma) after receiving varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) and Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R-II), the patient kept getting ear, chest infection and also had problems in "peeing". On 13-JUN-2018, the patient was then diagnosed with stage 3 sarcoma. On an unknown date, the patient experienced constipation and had infections as informed by the physician to the patient's mother. On an unknown date, the patient was hospitalized due to stage 3 sarcoma for a duration of 30 days for chemotherapy during his initial diagnosis. The patient was reportedly in and out of the hospital. The patient received 42 rounds of chemotherapy treatment for the event of sarcoma. On an unknown date, the patient developed a super bug and experienced a huge hemorrhage at the end of his treatment with chemotherapy. On unknown dates, the patient developed a nut allergy and an allergy to certain soaps. On an unknown date, the patient also experienced pneumonia like symptoms during his chemotherapy treatment. It was also reported that, the patient had no evidence of the disease in his body and the patient's mother did not know when her son had the reaction to vaccinations as a child and to which vaccinations. The patient sought medical attention by visiting the physician. The patient underwent hemoglobin studies, Epstein-barr virus test, treponema pallidium microhemoglobin, non-reactive regain antibodies, teardrop cells, platelet neuropathy and parvovirus B19 but the results of which were not provided. There was no product quality complaint associated with this report.  The outcome of all the events was reported to be recovered by the end of March 2019. The causality assessment was not provided.  Upon internal review, the events of sarcoma, pathogen resistance, lower respiratory tract infection, pneumonia and hemorrhage were determined to be medically significant.

On 1st October 2019, 1 days after receiving Shingrix, Havrix and FluLaval Tetra 2019-2020 season, the patient experienced ischemic optic neuropathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and headache. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix on right deltoid. The patient experienced headache and left ear pressure. The patient experienced bilateral ischemic optic neuropathy. The patient began to have eye symptoms of loss of left upper field of vision, in the left eye. Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Shoulder dystocia labor complication; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 10-Dec-2019, concerning a neonate, female subject, whose mother was a 31-year-old female, of body weight 133 lbs, height 66 inches and body mass index (BMI) 21.5, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy. The subject's father was 32-year-old.  The mother's medical history included hypothyroidism. Concomitant medications included Prenatal (unspecified vitamins and minerals), magnesium citrate and Synthroid (levothyroxine sodium) for hypothyroidism.   The mother's obstetrical history included three previous pregnancies: two spontaneous abortions and one full term live birth. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) was on 18-Feb-2019 and type of pregnancy was singleton. The estimated date of delivery (EDD) and corrected EDD (CEDD) of subject's mother were reported as 25-Nov-2020.  On 15-Apr-2019 and 03-Jul-2019, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.   On 18-Sep-2019, at approximately 30 weeks of gestation, the mother was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL (Afluria QIV) [influenza vaccine, batch number: P100118562, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunization.  On 04-Oct-2019 and 01-Nov-2019, the subject's mother underwent ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.  At gestational age of 40.1 weeks, the mother vaginally delivered live female neonate. The characteristics of neonate included birth weight: 4270 grams, head circumference: 35 cm and length: 55.9 cm. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) scores at one minute was 7 and at five minutes was 9. APGAR score at 10 minutes was not reported. The neonate experienced labour complication - shoulder dystocia.   At the time of initial reporting, the outcome of the event was not reported.  Per company, the event of shoulder dystocia was considered serious due to the criterion of medical significance.   The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  This case is linked to the case 201907228 (the corresponding mother case).  The female neonate subject experienced shoulder dystocia (labour complication) after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at 30 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. Causality between suspect product and the shoulder dystocia is assessed as not related due to biological implausibility.; Sender's Comments: The female neonate subject experienced shoulder dystocia (labour complication) after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria QIV. Reportedly, vaccination occurred during pregnancy at 30 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions. Causality between suspect product and the shoulder dystocia is assessed as not related due to biological implausibility.

She and her adult- daughter came to the pharmacy on 12/20/19 and showed me her left arm. It had developed a large, patch area that's a rash which itches and there is heat to touch. She reports it appeared yesterday (12/19). I told them it is common reaction from the Prevnar13 vaccine because that is where the rash appears to have stemmed from. I recommended cold compress over the area, hydrocortisone 1% cream OTC, and taking an antihistamine (Benadryl, Claritin, Zyrtec, or Allergra). Pt's daughter voiced understanding.

Around 5:00 p.m. I began feeling achy. At 6:00 I took my temperature, 100.3 and went to bed. My body was achy, had chills, fever and headache. The worst headache ever woke me around 3:00 a.m. I drank   water that was beside my bed thinking I was dehydrated. Around 5:00 I got up to take Advil. In the kitchen while getting water I fainted. My face must have hit first as it was bloody on the left side with a big upper lip. I then must have fell backward lacerating my head. When I gained consciousness my neck and head pain was severe. I could not roll over or move myself. I could move my hands and feet but couldn't grip with my hands. I tried to get up so I could get to the ER but was unable to move. Went by ambulance. It is nearly 2 months later and my neck is still immobile, headaches continue, fatigue is ever present despite of physical therapy. I was a very active person who walked 3 miles/day and practiced yoga. The financial cost even with insurance is nearing $10,000. I would rather have shingles. There is medicine to take which aids in a quick recovery of a shingles outbreak. I don't know to what extent I will ever recover from this shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient administered Flublock at 6:01 pm and had no initial reaction, but asked to sit in waiting room for 20 min after due to first flu immunization in over 10 years.  At 6:15 pm the wife called me over that the patient was feeling weird.  Patient was on the floor oriented but pale and mild perspiration on forehead. He did not complain of shortness of breath or pain, just dizzy and seeing spots. He said he felt unwell and lay down on the floor.  I took BP and it was 100/55 pulse 52 while supine. He was less pale at 6:20 pm BP 105/62 pulse 69. He wanted to move out of main waiting room and carefully we got him up into the treatment room where he returned to supine at 6:26 and bp 123/78 pulse 76.  He then felt like sitting up against the wall and stated he hadn't eaten all day so we got some orange juice for him to drink. At 6:33 pm BP was 125/85 pulse 78 and he was feeling much better, and a little embarrassed.  He moved to sitting in the chair with assistance and at 6:38 pm bp was 126-75 pulse 75 and he said he thought he would be ok to leave.  I checked and he did not have any shortness of breath, chest pain, or complain of any injury.  I took one final bp at 6:40 pm standing and it was 116/82 pulse 85.  He stated he would take it easy and go home to rest but he felt much better, no dizziness and would follow up with me if any other symptoms occurred.

upper respiratory infection; suffered left-sided facial weakness/diagnosed with Bell's Palsy; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a male patient of unknown age. The patient's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications were not reported. On or about 06-MAR-2017, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (exact dose, site and route of administration, lot# and expiration date were not reported) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered left-sided facial weakness and was diagnosed with Bell's Palsy as well as suffered an upper respiratory infection. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of the vaccination, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the vaccination, the patient had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered. The relatedness between the events and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was related.  The events of Bell's Palsy and upper respiratory infection were considered to be disabling. Upon internal review, the event of Bell's Palsy was considered to be medically significant.

Suspected vaccination failure; Influenza A; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of vaccination failure in a infant patient who received Flu Seasonal TIV Dresden (Flu trivalent vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal TIV Dresden (Flu trivalent vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Flu trivalent vaccine and the 2nd dose of Flu trivalent vaccine. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Flu trivalent vaccine and more than a week after receiving Flu trivalent vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and influenza a virus infection (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and influenza a virus infection were unknown.   The reporter considered the vaccination failure and influenza a virus infection to be related to Flu trivalent vaccine and Flu trivalent vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a patient aged less than 2 years of unspecified gender, who was vaccinated with unspecified trivalent inactivated influenza vaccine (TIV) (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.  This was a test-negative design study that examined data retrospectively over 3 influenza seasons. It was estimated vaccine effectiveness (VE) against influenza hospitalization among children aged 6 months to 8 years at hospitals in the 2015-2016, 2016-2017, and 2017-2018 influenza seasons, using the test-negative design. For each season, it was estimated VE for fully and partially vaccinated children, using complete vaccine receipt histories from birth. [Individuals were excluded if they received their vaccine less than 14 days before hospitalization, received the live attenuated influenza vaccine or quadrivalent inactivated vaccine (QIV) in the current influenza season, were hospitalized outside the influenza season, or were tested for influenza more than 10 days after hospital admission. It was considered the beginning of the season to be the week when the first influenza positive sample was reported, and the end of the season to be the week when sentinel surveillance ended, based on MoH surveillance. Comorbid conditions were defined for the 2 years before hospitalization. It was included 326 influenza-positive case patients and 2821 influenza-negative controls (140 case patients and 971 controls from 2015-2016, 36 case patients and 1069 controls from 2016-2017, and 150 case patients and 781 controls from 2017-2018)]. The patient did not receive the live attenuated influenza vaccine (LAIV) or quadrivalent inactivated vaccine (QIV) in the current influenza season. The patient were not hospitalized outside the influenza season. The patient had at least one comorbidity (unspecified) for the 2 years before hospitalization. No information on patient's medical history, family history, or concurrent condition was provided. On an unspecified date from 1 September of the 2016-2017 influenza season, the patient received full vaccination of unspecified trivalent inactivated influenza vaccine (TIV) (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. [Vaccination is the most effective strategy for prevention of influenza-related illness and is recommended annually by the Ministry of Health (MoH) and the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices for individuals aged more than or equal to 6 months. Both recommendations specify that children aged 6 months through 8 years receive 2 doses of influenza vaccine if they have not received more than 1 influenza vaccine previously. Vaccinated individuals were those who had received TIV from 1 September of the influenza season of interest and more than or equal to 14 days before hospital admission. Fully vaccinated individuals were those who had received a current season vaccine (TIV only) and had received more than or equal to 2 influenza vaccines previously, or had received 2 current season vaccines more than or equal to 14 days apart. Partially vaccinated individuals were those who had received a current season vaccine and did not meet the criteria for full vaccination. During 2016-2017, children in second grade received influenza vaccine in school, but records of these vaccinations were not routinely entered into the electronic medical record. To evaluate the impact of these potentially incomplete vaccination records, it was conducted 2 additional analyses; it was removed 2016-2017 data from the overall VE estimate, and estimated influenza VE in the 2016-2017 excluding individuals more than 5 years old as of 1 September 2016]. The patient received a current season vaccine (TIV only) and had received more than or equal to 2 influenza vaccines previously, or had received 2 current season vaccines more than or equal to 14 days apart. The patient received the vaccine more than or equal to 14 days before hospitalization. On an unspecified date between 8 October 2016 and 16 April 2017 in 2016-2017 influenza season, less than 10 days after hospital admission, the patient was tested for influenza. [Influenza case patients were individuals who tested positive for influenza by reverse-transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) during a hospital admission. The majority of these hospitalizations were in children who were male (55.2%), aged 6 months to less than 2 years old (60.7%), and had more than or equal to 1 comorbid condition (54.3%). The 2016-2017 season had few positive specimens (n = 36), all influenza A. The 2015-16 season occurred between 11 October 2015 and 16 April 2016, the 2016-17 season between 8 October 2016 and 16 April 2017. For the 2017-18 season, it was included hospitalizations from 21 October 2017 through 18 March 2018, the latest date that data were available at the time of analysis, and three weeks before the end of the influenza season]. The patient had tested positive for influenza A by RT-PCR during hospital admission. This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown. This case has been considered as serious due to suspected vaccination failure and hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not reported. The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of influenza A infection and unspecified trivalent inactivated influenza vaccine (TIV). The author stated, "This study, the first to evaluate influenza VE against hospitalization, found that influenza vaccine was effective in preventing hospitalization associated with laboratory-confirmed influenza in fully vaccinated children aged 6 months to 8 years across 3 influenza seasons. Among fully vaccinated children, the vaccine was effective against influenza A in 2 of 3 seasons and against influenza B in 2017-2018. Estimated VE for partial vaccination was consistently lower than VE for full vaccination. Young children are at high risk for severe influenza-related outcomes, including hospitalization and death. Delayed hospital presentation could increase the likelihood of false-negative RT-PCR results if the infection has cleared before testing. VE. To reduce inclusion of false-negative results, it was excluded individuals who were tested more than 10 days after hospital admission. It was included individuals tested up to 10 days before admission because previous study findings suggest that children may shed influenza for a long time, with a substantial decrease in shedding after 10 days." The author concluded, "It was found influenza vaccine to be effective against hospitalization for laboratory-confirmed influenza in fully vaccinated children aged 6 months to 8 years from 2015 to 2018. The VE for partial vaccination was consistently lower than for full vaccination. There was also high VE against influenza A in 2015-2016 and 2016-2017 and against influenza B in 2017-2018. It was found evidence for cross-lineage protection from vaccination when TIV included B/Victoria but not when TIV included B/Yamagata, though these estimates rely on small sample sizes and have wide CIs. The findings suggesting that influenza VE reduces the risk for severe disease in children further strengthen current recommendations for annual influenza vaccine in children. The higher VE for children who were fully vaccinated is consistent with current guidelines that recommend 2 vaccines for vaccine-naive children through age 8." This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in the same literature article.      Lab Comments: Lab test done on an unspecified date between 8 October 2016 and 16 April 2017.

Lupus; autoimmune hepatitis; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation, concerning a female patient (pt) of unknown age. The pt's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications were not reported.   In or around 03-NOV-2016, the pt was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose of prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot number and expiration date were not reported).   In approximately December 2016 (approximately one month after receiving the vaccine), the pt suffered and was diagnosed with lupus and autoimmune hepatitis. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. The pt was looking for compensatory damages for past, present, and future damages, including but not limited to pain and suffering for severe and permanent personal injuries, health and medical care costs, lost wages, together with interest and costs as provided by law.   The outcome of the events was not recovered. The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).   Upon internal review, lupus and autoimmune hepatitis were considered to be disabling and medically significant events.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Six hrs after injection I began to feel a malaise that intensified such that the following morning, I had to cancel a meeting.   About 24 hrs after injection, I began to experience intestinal distress with periods of cramps. The distress came in the form of either diarrhea or constipation where each alternating symptom would last for several days. The severity of the symptoms became less intense after about 30 days. However, the symptoms 60 days later are less severe but still continue. There is also a lack of energy that persists, and tiredness.  The feeling is my sense that I'm not fully free of the effects that began after the injection. On the day of the injection, my wife also had the shingrix and fluzone vaccine, and my son had just the fluzone. My wife has experienced similar symptoms to myself which also continue 60 days later. My son did not have any symptoms from which we inferred the Shingrix was the cause of our symptoms and not the Fluzone.
LAB_DATA: No medical tests done.  Dr indicated that our symptoms were not typical of the Shingrix vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On day #1, at 4 PM, I felt chills all over my body, followed shortly thereafter by uncontrollable shaking. My wife put me in bed and covered me with multiple layers of blankets, and the shaking stopped that night. On day #2, I woke with almost complete loss of strength in my legs, such that I could not get out of my chair and could only stand briefly. Later that day, I could not stand at all without assistance. My temperature rose to 101.5. I had no energy and my entire body ached. At 6:30 PM I was taken by Rescue Squad to the emergency room of Hospital. The staff tested my blood and urine and took chest X-rays, all of which were normal. I was released at 9:30 PM, without any new medication and with a diagnosis that the symptoms were likely the result of the vaccination. Back home, I developed new symptoms of excessive gas and diarrhea. On day #3, I woke up with my pajamas drenched with perspiration and with a return to normal body temperature. The gas and diarrhea continued, but strength began to return to my legs. I only wanted to remain sedentary, even though I normally am very active and high energy.  Today is day #4, and the diarrhea is gone, but some abnormal amount of gas remains. I am able to walk down the driveway  to the mailbox.
OTHER_MEDS: losartan HCTZ, simvastatin, finasteride, meloxicam, generic Zyrtex, terazosin

Injection site was raised and irritated the day following injection (12/13) with worsening 2 days after receiving the shot. On 12/14, I noticed the area was raised, red, itchy, and bruised. The affected area around the injection site was about 2-2.5? in diameter. I applied hydrocortisone cream and applied ice to the area.  The area did go down, but on 12/19 she woke up with hive-like spots on her back and torso and had congestion. I gave her a decongestant before I realized she had hives. The rash became more red and itchy, and eventually made its way to her face. Zyrtec given at 12:00 with further evaluation from her pediatrician later that afternoon. Benadryl given at 12:00 midnight and again at 6 AM with no relief. The next day the rash had tripled in size and covered the majority of her trunk, limbs, and almost all of her face. Decreased appetite and fever now accompanied the rash. She was taken to the ER after I noticed she was biting her lips and was experiencing facial swelling. The initial injection site was also raised and itchy outside of the area that was first affected. ER gave her a dose of oral prednisone, Benadryl, and Motrin to combat fever. Antibiotic was switched to Zithromax and we were discharged. The next day there was no improvement. The areas of skin first affected by the rash were now darkening and turning more purple, but newer areas were pink. She was taken back to her pediatrician where she was evaluated. Her pediatrician advised we take her to the emergency room to be treated for HSP. ER physician suspected serum sickness. She was treated with IV fluids, IV steroids, hydroxyzine.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests were run at the ER on 12/20
CUR_ILL: Being treated for vaginal strep A, initial symptoms began 12/9. Treatment with amoxicillin began 12/10 with flu shot 12/12 at yearly checkup.
HISTORY: Tested positive for vaginal strep A twice since October 2019, both treated with amoxicillin.

Arrest of dilation; Failure to descend; Yeast / vaginal itching; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational pregnancy study case, initially received from other health professional on 12-Dec-2019, concerning a 21-year-old, adult, female pregnant subject of body weight: 160 lbs, height: 61.2 inches and body mass index (BMI): 30, enrolled in a prospective observational study.  The subject's current medical conditions included obesity (BMI 30) and iron deficiency.   The subject's concomitant medications included Fusion Plus (ascorbic acid, biotin, cyanocobalamin, ferrous fumarate, folic acid, lactobacillus casei, nicotinic acid, pantothenic acid, polysaccharide-iron complex, pyridoxine hydrochloride, riboflavin, thiamine hydrochloride) for iron deficiency and Prenatal vitamins (minerals nos, vitamins nos) for OB (obstetrical) supplement.   The subject's obstetrical history included no previous pregnancies. The subject did not have a history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM).  Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 20-Feb-2019, estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 27-Nov-2020. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   On an unknown date, the pregnancy status was collected, and no pregnancy complications were noted. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 17-May-2019, the subject underwent first trimester screen and nuchal translucency and no MCM was noted.   On 19-May-2019, the subject underwent second trimester screen and MSFAP (maternal serum alpha-fetoproteins) / serum markers and no major congenital malformation was noted.   On 09-Jul-2019, the subject underwent anatomy ultrasound and no major congenital malformation was noted.   On 20-Sep-2019, at 30 weeks of gestation, the subject was administered Flucelvax QIVc (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261200, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, expiry date and anatomical location: not reported] for influenza immunisation (explicitly coded as �Vaccine exposure during pregnancy').  On 24-Sep-2019, four days after vaccination, the subject developed yeast/vaginal itching. The subject was treated with metronidazole (1 applicator, every day, administered vaginally, start date: 24-Sep-2019, stop date: 29-Sep-2019) and fluconazole (1 tablet, every day, administered orally, start date: 24-Sep-2019, stop date: 25-Sep-2019).   On 29-Sep-2019, the subject recovered from yeast/vaginal itching.   At 39.5 weeks of gestation, the subject gave a live birth to a normal male neonate, by caesarean delivery (per reporter delivery was complicated by �failure to descend, oligohydramnios, arrest of dilation). The neonate's birth weight was 3402 grams, head circumference and body length were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) scores were 9 (at one minute) and 9 (at five minutes). APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. There was no major congenital malformation identified at birth.   At the time of initial report, outcomes of the events �cervix dystocia' and �arrested labor' were not reported.   The event of �cervix dystocia' and �arrested labor' were considered as serious, due to the criterion of medical significance, per company.   The reporter did not provide causality assessment.   This case is linked to 201907307 (corresponding baby case).  Company comment: The patient developed vulvovaginal mycotic infection, 4 days after vaccination with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. Vaccine was administered at 30 weeks of gestation, which was coded as vaccine exposure during pregnancy. Chronology is plausible. Reportedly, delivery was complicated by cervix dystocia and arrested labour. Causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be excluded and is assessed as related for the events of vulvovaginal mycotic infection, cervix dystocia and arrested labour. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: The patient developed vulvovaginal mycotic infection, 4 days after vaccination with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Oligohydramnios; Foetal exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 12-Dec-2019 with additional information received on 16-Dec-2019  (being processed together), concerning a male neonate whose mother was a 21-year-old subject of body weight: 160 lbs, height: 61.2 inches and body mass index (BMI): 30,  enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's mother current conditions included obesity (body mass index 30) and iron deficiency.  The subject's mother concomitant medications Prenatal vitamins (minerals nos, vitamins nos) for OB (obstetrical care) and Fusion plus (ascorbic acid, biotin, cyanocobalamin, ferrous fumarate, folic acid, lactobacillus casei, nicotinic acid, pantothenic acid, polysaccharide-iron complex, pyridoxine hydrochloride, riboflavin, thiamine hydrochloride) for iron deficiency.  The subject's mother did not have previous pregnancies. The subject's mother did not have any history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no paternal or maternal history with MCMs. The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The paternal age was 24-year-old.  The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was on 20-Feb-2019, estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected EDD (CEDD) was 27-Nov-2019. The pregnancy was singleton.   On 17-May-2019, nuchal translucency and first trimester screen were performed, no major MCMs was noted.  On 19-May-2019, second trimester screen and maternal serum alpha fetoprotein (MSAFP, serum markers) were performed, no major MCMs was noted.  On 09-Jul-2019, anatomy ultrasound was performed, no major MCMs was noted.  On 20-Sep-2019, at approximately 30 weeks of gestation, the subject received Flucelvax QIVc [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, batch number: 261200, route of administration, expiry date and anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation.  On 24-Sep-2019, the subject's mother developed yeast/vaginal itching, and was treated with metronidazole and fluconazole.  On an unspecified date in 2019, the oligohydramnios was noted.  At 39.5 weeks of gestational age, the subject's mother delivered live male neonate via caesarean method of delivery (per reporter �failure to descend, oligohydramnios and arrest of dilation'). Neonate's birth weight was 3402 grams, body length and head circumference were not reported and the appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) score one minute: 9, five minutes: 9 and ten minutes: not reported. There was no MCM identified at birth.  The event of oligohydramnios was assessed as serious due to medically significance per the company.   This case is linked with case 201907304 corresponding mother case.  Company comment: The subject's mother received vaccine at approximately 30 weeks of gestation. Oligohydramnios may also develop in a third trimester of pregnancy, however it is unknown when this adverse event was initially noted. Causality assessment is confounded by mother's obesity. Based on the currently available information the causal relationship between Flucelvax and oligohydramnios is considered unassessable. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is unrelated to Flucelvax.; Sender's Comments: The subject's mother received vaccine at approximately 30 weeks of gestation. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Stillbirth; Low birth weight; Premature birth; This is an observational study case, initially received from other health professional on 16-Dec-2019 with an additional information received on 18-Dec-2019 (being processed together), concerning a male, neonatal subject. The subject's mother was 33-year-old  pregnant female of body weight: 246 Ibs, height: 67 in and body mass index (BMI) 38.5 enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's mother current medical condition included history of venous thromboembolism, gestational hypertension (GHTN), anxiety, nausea, vomiting, history of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and obesity.   The subject's mother concomitant medication included Prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins and minerals) for pregnancy, Lexapro (escitalopram oxalate) for anxiety, promethazine for nausea and vomiting and Lovenox (enoxaparin sodium) for history of venous thromboembolism.  The subject's mother had no previous pregnancies. The subject's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs). The subject's mother had no history of offspring with MCM. The subject's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's mother last menstrual period (LMP) date was 24-Jun-2019. Estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 30-Mar-2020 and corrected estimated delivery date (CEDD) was not reported.   The type of pregnancy was singleton.    On 18-Sep-2019, the subject's mother underwent first sequential and nuchal translucency. No MCMs were noted.  On 16-Oct-2019, at approximately 16 weeks of gestation, the subject's mother was administered Afluria QIV [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, cell cultured derived, batch number: P100112488, dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.  On the same day, the subject's mother underwent second sequential and no MCMs were noted.  On 30-Oct-2019, the subject's mother underwent early glucose tolerance test and per reporter, it failed.  On 04-Nov-2019, the subject's mother underwent three-hour glucose tolerance test and no MCMs were noted.  At approximately 22 weeks of gestation, mother vaginally delivered a stillbirth male neonate, (explicitly coded as 'Premature birth'). The pregnancy outcome was stillbirth. The characteristics of the neonate included weight: 417 grams, head circumference and length were not reported. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were not reported. No MCMs were identified at the time of birth. On the same day, the subject's mother was diagnosed with HELLP syndrome (characterised with hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and a low platelet count). It was reported that the factors that may had impact on fetal loss included mother's HELLP syndrome and history of DVT. It was unknown whether the autopsy was performed.  The event of stillbirth is considered as serious due to fatal outcome, while the events of low birth weight baby and premature birth are considered as serious due to criterion of medical significance.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  This case is linked to case 201907406 (corresponding mother case).  Company comment: The patient experienced preterm birth and low birth weight, one months and 14 days after maternal receipt of Afluria QIV. The pregnancy outcome was stillbirth. The subject's mother was administered vaccine at approximately 16 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. Mother's medical history of venous thromboembolism, gestational hypertension and concomitant drugs used during pregnancy may have contributed to development of the events. However, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related. The event foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related to the suspect vaccine.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced preterm birth and low birth weight, one months and 14 days after maternal receipt of Afluria QIV. Received vaccine at urgent care.  There was no pain at injection site.  I recall that it was in the left arm, however, consent form states right arm.  Symptoms occurred about a week later.  At first I had neck spasms and thought it might be the way I was sleeping.  I took Ibuprofen at night for over a week.  I noted pain in upper arm and in forearm.  I am not on any meds and I continued taking Ibuprofen and alternating nights with acetaminophen.  Approximately 2 months later I still have some upper arm pain.  I contacted NP on 12/23/19 just to inquire as to whether other employees had symptoms.  She stated that the have 3-5/year out of 3000 employees who have indicated similar discomfort. I elected not to go to clinic as it appeared to be improving.  Treatment that might have been used would be steroids that would have affected my blood glucose as I am pre diabetic and maintain my fasting blood glucose at ~115 mg/dl for past 15 years.  I am going to consider other locations for receiving vaccine in future as this has been uncomfortable and I question doing physical activities that require lifting and/or upper body strength.

Elevated liver enzymes; Abnormal glucose tolerance test; Cholestasis; Anemia; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; Prenatal test abnormality-positive for open spina bifida; This is spontaneous case, initially received from other health professional on 09-Dec-2019, concerning a 29-year-old pregnant female patient of body weight 220 pounds, height 66 inches and body mass index (BMI) 35.5. The paternal age was 30 years.   The patient's medical history included: anxiety, obesity, nausea and gastroesophageal reflux disease.  The patient's concomitant medication included: Zantac (ranitidine hydrochloride) for gastroesophageal reflux disease, Multivitamin (vitamins nos) for vitamin as reported and promethazine for nausea.   The patient's obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy with one full term live birth. The patient had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal and paternal medical history. The mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The patient's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 21-Apr-2019. The type of pregnancy was multiple (mono/di). The patient's estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 24-Jan-2020 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 24-Jan-2020.   On 11-Jun-2019, the patient underwent ultrasound scan and MCM was noted.  On 22-Jul-2019, the patient underwent first trimester screen and nuchal translucency screen and no MCM was noted.  On 12-Aug-2019, the patient had MSAFP/serum markers analysis and no MCM was noted. On the same day the patient underwent second trimester screen and results were positive for open spina bifida.   On 14-Aug-2019 the patient underwent ultrasound scan and MCM was noted.  On 11-Sep-2019, the patient underwent anatomy ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.   On 11-Sep-2019, approximately at 20 weeks of gestation, the patient was administered Flucelvax QIV [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent; batch number: 261200; dose, route of administration, anatomical location and expiration date: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an unknown indication.   On 23-Oct-2019, the patient developed anaemia and was treated with Iron, at single dose, intravenous and Ferralet 90 (ascorbic acid, cyanocobalamin, docusate sodium, ferrous gluconate, folic acid, iron pentacarbonyl), at dose of one tablet, orally, every day.   On 06-Nov-2019 the patient developed cholestasis and was treated with Actigall (ursodeoxycholic acid) at dose of 300 mg, one capsule every four hours, orally.  On 08-Nov-2019, glucose tolerance test was abnormal.   On 20-Nov-2019, liver enzymes were elevated.   Outcome of the events of cholestasis, anemia, abnormal glucose tolerance test and elevated liver enzymes was not recovered. Outcome of the events of prenatal screening test abnormal and vaccine exposure during pregnancy was not reported.   The event of prenatal screening test abnormal and cholestasis were considered serious due to the criterion of medical significance.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  Company comment: The patient experienced cholestasis and glucose tolerance test abnormal, 1 month and 26 days after vaccination with Flucelvax QIV, administered at approximately 20 weeks of gestation. The patient also experienced anaemia 1 month 12 days after vaccination and hepatic enzyme increased 2 months after. Although causality was confounded by medical history of obesity, chronology is plausible and causality is assessed as related to these events. Reportedly, one month before vaccination, results were positive for open spina bifida. Chronology is implausible and causality is assessed as not related for prenatal screening test abnormal. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy as not related to suspect vaccine.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced cholestasis and glucose tolerance test abnormal, 1 month and 26 days after vaccination with Flucelvax QIV, administered at approximately 20 weeks of gestation. This persisted for about 3 days.  Day 2, I felt much better but still was slightly fatigues and ibuprofen was no longer needed.  On Days 3 to 5, I notice I was emotionally unsettled feeling - kind of irritable and upset feeling.  I never felt this way before to my knowledge.  After Day 5 symptoms resolved except for the site of injection redness, soreness, and fever still resolving. By Day 7 I was back to normal.
LAB_DATA: I did not seek medical attention, and I believe it was not needed.

I reported the adverse event to the pharmacist during the visit for the second injection to both the person running the cashier and the person who injected me with the booster.

primary cutaneous CD4+ small/medium T-cell lymphoproliferative disorder; red lesion started to form in the stomach; lesion started to form in the stomach and itched; Pseudolymphoma; lymph node of mild concern; lymphnode benign; suspicious of an Atypical T-cell infiltrate; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of lymphoproliferative disorder in a adult male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 9th August 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. In September 2019, less than 2 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced lymphoproliferative disorder (serious criteria GSK medically significant), skin lesion, pruritus, pseudolymphoma, lymph node disorder, benign lymph node neoplasm and lymphocytic infiltration. The patient was treated with topical antibiotic (nos) (Antibiotic Cream (Nos)). On an unknown date, the outcome of the lymphoproliferative disorder, skin lesion, pruritus, pseudolymphoma, lymph node disorder, benign lymph node neoplasm and lymphocytic infiltration were unknown.   The reporter considered the lymphoproliferative disorder, skin lesion, pruritus, pseudolymphoma, lymph node disorder, benign lymph node neoplasm and lymphocytic infiltration to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient was self reporting what he believed dould be a side effect from Shingrix. Four to 5 weeks after the vaccination, the patient thought that could have have received an insect bite to stomach as a red lesion started to form and it itched. The patient had punch biopsy with a result of suspicious for an atypical T-cell infiltrate. The patient preformed blood test with normal result and performed PET scan which showed one lymph node of mild concern which later tested benign after removal and biopsy as per oncologist suggested. The patient had concurrent flow cytometry with no immunophenotypic evidence of a clonal cell population and bone marrow biopsy or aspiration with no changes of concern for lymphoma. The patient had entire lesion excised from the stomach and was biopsied, it showed similar features to the punch biopsy by morphology and immunohistochemistry. Till the time of reporting the lesions did not go away and requested that a doctor look at it. The doctor prescribed a topical antibiotic cream and after 5 days the patient did not notice a change in the lesion, so the patient had requested a dermatologist examine it and took a punch biopsy and was subsequently referred to an oncologist. The patient reported that, the oncology and pathology departments have diagnosed condition as a primary cutaneous CD4+ small or medium T-cell lymphoproliferative disorder. The patient asked if, it was possible that the Shingrix vaccine caused the lesion (pseudolymphoma) and should get 2nd dose of Shingrix as currently due for 2nd dose. The patient also asked if there were other similar cases to what had experienced. The reporter consented to follow up to get a sense of whether this was a disorder that needed to worry about for the rest of life or was it more likely that this was a reaction to the vaccine.      Lab Comments: The punch biopsy result was suspicious for an Atypical T-cell infiltrate. The entire lesion was excised from the stomach and was biopsied. It showed similar features to the punch biopsy by morphology and immunohistochemistry. The concurrent flow cytometry shows no immunophenotypic evidence of a clonal cell population. The PET scan which showed one lymphnode of mild concern which later tested benign after removal and biopsy.

Pre-eclampsia; Low-lying placenta; Preterm birth; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case initially received from other health professional on 21-Oct-2019, concerning a 37-year-old female, pregnant subject of body weight 121 lbs, height 61 in and body mass index (BMI) 22.9, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.   The subject's relevant medical history included acid reflux and advanced maternal age.   The subject's concomitant medications included: Prenatal and DHA (docosahexaenoic acid) vitamins (ascorbic acid, betacarotene, calcium carbonate, colecalciferol, docosahexaenoic acid, ferrous fumarate, folic acid, nicotinamide, pyridoxine hydrochloride, riboflavin, thiamine mononitrate, tocopheryl acetate, vitamin b12 nos, zinc oxide), iron, vitamin D3 and omeprazole for acid reflux.  The subject's obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy which ended with elective abortion. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no relevant maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 06-Mar-2019. The subject's estimated date of delivery (EDD) was reported as 11-Dec-2019 and corrected EDD (CEDD) was reported as 31-Dec-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 04-Jun-2019, the subject underwent ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.  On 07-Aug-2019, the subject underwent maternal serum alpha fetoprotein (MSAFP)/serum markers test and no MCM was noted.  On 06-Sep-2019, the subject underwent foetal echo test and no MCM was noted.  On 30-Sep-2019, at approximately 26 weeks and 6 days of gestation, the subject was administered Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL (Afluria QIV) [influenza vaccine, batch number: P100118566, dose, expiration date, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunization.  At 35.3 weeks of gestation, the subject gave live birth to male neonate by caesarean method. The neonate's body weight was 2410 grams, head circumference 33 cm and length 45 cm.  The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). No data was provided for Apgar score in 10 minutes. There was no major congenital malformation identified at birth. The pregnancy complications were noted as severe pre-eclampsia and low-lying placenta.   The outcome of the events 'pre-eclampsia', 'premature delivery' and 'placenta praevia' was not reported.  The events of 'pre-eclampsia', 'premature delivery' and 'placenta praevia' were considered serious due to the criteria of medical significance, per company.   The causality assessment was not provided.    This case is linked to 201907404 (corresponding child case).  Follow up received from other health professional on 18-Dec-2019: Occupation deleted. Pregnancy information added. Facility type changed. Gestational period at exposure for concomitant medications and suspect product changed. Omeprazole added as concomitant medication. Three new events added 'low-lying placenta', 'premature delivery' and 'pre-eclampsia'. Outcome of 'vaccine exposure during pregnancy' changed to recovered/resolved and stop date updated. Narrative amended accordingly.  Company comment: The subject experienced placenta praevia, pre-eclampsia and premature delivery associated with administration of Afluria QIV. The patient was administered vaccine at approximately 26 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. For the event placenta praevia, chronology does not seem plausible and causality is assessed as not related. Although causality for all events was confounded by advanced maternal age, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as related for pre-eclampsia and premature delivery. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: The subject experienced placenta praevia, pre-eclampsia and premature delivery associated with administration of Afluria QIV. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was showing no symptoms and was in good mood until right before he went unconscious. The ASM immediately called 911 and I talked to the patient and asked how he felt and whether he was having difficulty breathing. There were no signs of SOB or anaphylactic reaction.
